# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: maritime-history
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The **1982 Lebanon War**, also called the **Second Israeli invasion of Lebanon**, began on 6 June 1982, when Israel invaded southern Lebanon.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The invasion followed a series of attacks and counter-attacks between the Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO) operating in southern Lebanon and the Israel Defense Forces (IDF), which had caused civilian casualties on both sides of the border.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israeli military operation, codenamed **Operation Peace for Galilee**, was launched after gunmen from the Abu Nidal Organization attempted to assassinate Shlomo Argov, Israel's ambassador to the United Kingdom.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israeli prime minister Menachem Begin blamed the PLO, using the incident as a *casus belli*.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] It was the second invasion of Lebanon by Israel, following the 1978 South Lebanon conflict.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israelis sought to end Palestinian attacks from Lebanon, destroy the Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO) in the country, and install a pro-Israel Maronite Christian government.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israeli forces attacked and overran PLO positions in southern Lebanon and briefly clashed with the Syrian Army, who occupied most of the country's northeast.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israeli military, together with the South Lebanon Army, seized control of the southern half of Lebanon and laid siege to the capital Beirut.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Lebanese Forces however, despite their clandestine alliance with Israel, refused to participate in the war against the PLO as their leader Bachir Gemayel viewed any direct involvement as assisting an invading army.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Surrounded in West Beirut and subjected to heavy Israeli bombardment, the PLO and their allies negotiated a ceasefire with the aid of United States special envoy Philip Habib.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The PLO, led by Yasser Arafat, were evacuated from Lebanon, overseen by a multinational peacekeeping force.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] By expelling the PLO, removing Syrian influence over Lebanon, and installing a pro-Israeli Christian government led by President Bachir Gemayel, the Israeli government hoped to sign a treaty that would give Israel "forty years of peace".
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Following the assassination of Gemayel in September 1982, Israel's position in Beirut became untenable and the signing of a peace treaty became increasingly unlikely.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] There was outrage at the IDF's role in the Israeli-backed, Phalangist-perpetrated Sabra and Shatila massacre of Palestinians and Lebanese Shias.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] This stoked Israeli public disillusionment with the war.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The IDF withdrew from Beirut and ended its operation on 29 September 1982.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The May 17 Agreement of 1983 ended the state of war between Israel and Lebanon, and provided for an Israeli withdrawal from the country.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Amid rising casualties from guerrilla attacks, the IDF retreated south of the Awali river on 3 September 1983.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] From February to April 1985, the Israeli military undertook a phased withdrawal to its "South Lebanon security zone" along the border.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israeli occupation saw the emergence of Hezbollah, an Iranian-backed Shia Islamist group.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] It waged a guerrilla war against the Israeli occupation until the IDF's final withdrawal from Lebanon in 2000.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In Israel, the 1982 invasion is also known as the **First Lebanon War**.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] During the 1948 Palestine war, 730,000 Palestinians fled or were forced to leave by Zionist forces, of whom 100,000 arrived in Lebanon.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Most of the guerrillas would be recruited from Palestinian refugee camps.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] By 1969, this population had grown to 235,000 as a result of natural population growth and immigration, including Palestinians who fled or were expelled by Israel during the 1967 war.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] On the eve of the 1982 Israeli invasion, the Palestinian population in Lebanon was 375,000.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The 1967 Six-Day War stimulated the growth of the Palestinian fedayeen (guerrillas).
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] After 1967, the number of armed Palestinians increased from 200 to 2,000 and by 1968 it had reached 15,000.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Palestinian guerrilla action intended to serve as a war of national liberation for Palestinians.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In 1968, PLO's objective was to establish a single democratic state in all of historical Palestine with equal rights for Jews, Muslims and Christians.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] It was around this time that Palestinians began to conduct raids into Israel.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] By 1977, the objective had evolved to establishing a Palestinian state in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, alongside Israel.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In 1970, a large influx of Palestinians from Jordan went into Lebanon after the Black September conflict.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] This caused an additional demographic imbalance within Lebanese society, and affected its democratic institutions established earlier by the National Pact.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] By 1975, the refugees numbered more than 300,000 and the PLO in effect created an unofficial state-within-a-state, particularly in Southern Lebanon, which then played an important role in the Lebanese Civil War.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] There had been continual violence near the Lebanon-Israel border between Israel and the PLO, starting from 1968; this increased following the relocation of PLO bases to Lebanon after the civil war in Jordan.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The violence between Israel and the PLO peaked during Operation Litani in 1978, provoked by the Coastal Road Massacre which was carried out by Palestinian militants.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] As early as 1976, Israel had been assisting Lebanese Christian militias in their sporadic battles against the PLO.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] During Operation Litani in 1978, Israel established a security zone in southern Lebanon with mostly Christian inhabitants, in which they began to supply training and arms to Christian militias which would later form the South Lebanese Army.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] But Israel's main partner was to be the Maronite Phalange party, whose paramilitary was led by Bashir Gemayel, a rising figure in Lebanese politics.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Gemayel's strategy during the early stages of the Lebanese Civil War was to provoke the Syrians into retaliatory attacks on Christians, such that Israel could not ignore.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In 1978, Menachem Begin declared that Israel would not allow a genocide of Lebanese Christians, while refusing direct intervention.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Hundreds of Lebanese militiamen began to train in Israel, at the IDF Staff and Command College.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] From June to December 1980, the United Nations Interim Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL) recorded an increase in activities along the border zone.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] No attacks by Palestinian forces on Israel were recorded, while the IDF incursions across the armistice line into Lebanon increased markedly, with minefields being laid, gun posts established, and generally involving numerous violations of Lebanese air-space and territorial waters.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] This was formally protested by the Lebanese government to the UN Security Council and General Assembly in several communications as violations by Israel of United Nations Security Council Resolution 425.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] During the same period Israel protested numerous attacks by Palestinian forces, unrelated to the Lebanese border zone.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In his report for the period of 12 December 1980 to 12 June 1981 on UNIFIL activities, the Security Council Secretary General noted that infiltrations into the border zone by Palestinian armed forces had decreased relative to the previous six months.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Indeed, the PLO had recognized their vulnerable position, and avoided overtly provoking Israel.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In contrast the IDF had launched various attacks on Lebanese territory often in support of the Lebanese Christian militia.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In doing so Israel had violated UN Security Council resolution 425 on hundreds of occasions [paragraph 58].
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Where the initiator(s) of attacks could be identified in the report, in 15 cases Palestinian militants were to blame while on 23 occasions the Militia and/or the IDF were the instigators, the latter also being responsible for the most violent confrontation of the period on 27 April [paragraph 52].
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] From 16 June to 10 December 1981, a relative quiet was reported continuing from 29 May 1981 until 10 July.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] This was broken when "Israeli aircraft resumed strikes against targets in southern Lebanon north of the UNIFIL area.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] (The Israeli strikes) led to exchanges of heavy firing between armed elements (Palestinians), on the one hand, and IDF and the de facto forces (Christian Militia) on the other.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] On 13 and 14 July, widespread Israeli air-strikes continued.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Armed elements (Palestinians) fired into the enclave and northern Israel." Israeli-initiated attacks had led to rocket and artillery fire on northern Israel.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] This pattern continued in the coming days.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israel renewed its air strikes in an attempt to trigger a war that would allow it to drive out the PLO and restore peace to the region.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] On 17 July, the Israel Air Force launched a massive attack on PLO buildings in downtown Beirut.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] "Perhaps as many as three hundred died, and eight hundred were wounded, the great majority of them civilians." The Israeli army also heavily targeted PLO positions in south Lebanon without success in suppressing Palestinian rocket launchers and guns.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] As a result, thousands of Israeli citizens who lived near the Lebanese border headed south.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] On 24 July 1981, United States Undersecretary of State Philip Habib brokered a ceasefire badly needed by both parties, the best achievable result from negotiations via intermediaries, aimed at complying with the decisions of UN Security Council resolution 490.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Between July 1981 and June 1982, as a result of the Habib ceasefire, the Lebanese-Israeli border "enjoyed a state of calm unprecedented since 1968." But the 'calm' was tense.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] US Secretary of State, Alexander Haig filed a report with US President Ronald Reagan on Saturday 30 January 1982 that revealed Secretary Haig's fear that Israel might, at the slightest provocation, start a war against Lebanon.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Then, on 21 April 1982, after a landmine killed an Israeli officer while he was visiting a South Lebanese Army gun emplacement in Taibe, Lebanon, the Israeli Air Force attacked the Palestinian-controlled coastal town of Damour, killing 23 people.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Fisk reports further on this incident: "The Israelis did not say what the soldier was doing ...
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] I discovered that he was visiting one of Haddad's artillery positions (Christian militia) and that the mine could have been lain [sic] as long ago as 1978, perhaps even by the Israelis themselves".
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] On 9 May 1982, Israeli aircraft again attacked targets in Lebanon.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Later that same day, UNIFIL observed the firing of rockets from Palestinian positions in the Tyre region into northern Israel, but none of the projectiles hit Israeli towns – the gunners had been ordered to miss.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Major-General Erskine (Ghana), Chief of Staff of UNTSO reported to the Secretary-General and the Security Council (S/14789, S/15194) that from August 1981 to May 1982, inclusive, there were 2096 violations of Lebanese airspace and 652 violations of Lebanese territorial waters.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The freedom of movement of UNIFIL personnel and UNTSO observers within the enclave remained restricted due to the actions of Amal and the South Lebanon Army under Major Saad Haddad's leadership with the backing of Israeli military forces.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Prior to establishing ceasefire in July 1981, U.N.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] I deeply deplore the extensive human suffering caused by these developments." The President of the U.N.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Security Council, Ide Oumarou of Niger, expressed "deep concern at the extent of the loss of life and the scale of the destruction caused by the deplorable events that have been taking place for several days in Lebanon".
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] From the ceasefire, established in July 1981, until the start of the war, the Israeli government reported 270 militant attacks by the PLO in Israel, the occupied territories, and the Jordanian and Lebanese border (in addition to 20 attacks on Israeli interests abroad).
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Arafat pressured the radical factions to maintain the ceasefire because he did not wish to provoke the Israelis into an all-out attack.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The PLO acceptance of the ceasefire had led to dissension even within Fatah itself.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] A faction sympathetic to Abu Nidal forced a military confrontation, with accompanying arrests and executions — an event unprecedented in PLO internal disputes'.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Arafat even attempted to distance himself from Palestinian unrest on the West Bank to prevent an Israeli attack.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In contrast, Begin, Sharon and Eitan were searching for any excuse to neutralize their military opponents through a breach of the ceasefire.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] They believed that Arafat was buying time to build up his conventional forces.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israeli interpretation of the conditions for the ceasefire placed responsibility for any act of Palestinian violence on Arafat's shoulders.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] It presumed that Arafat had complete control, not only over all factions within the PLO such as the rejectionist Popular Front of George Habash, but also over those outside such as Abu Nidal's Fatah Revolutionary Council and Ahmed Jibril's Popular Front — General Command.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In Begin's eyes, the ceasefire was not geographically limited to the Lebanese border.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] He argued that if Palestinian terrorism struck internationally, then this too would be regarded as a breach of the ceasefire.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Begin thus took a stand-off in a local battle as applying to the entire war anywhere in the Middle East or any incident internationally.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Eitan commented that there was no difference if a militant threw a grenade in Gaza or fired a shell at a Northern settlement — all such acts broke the ceasefire.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Sharon similarly did not wish to draw distinctions between different Palestinian factions, since all blame had to be attached to the PLO.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] He dismissed attempts at more rational evaluation as masking the real issue.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In a speech to a Young Herut conference in April 1982, he accused those who tried to take a more objective standpoint of erecting 'a protective wall around the PLO inside and outside Israel'.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Further support comes from George Ball, that the PLO had observed the ceasefire.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israel, he said, continued looking for the "internationally recognized provocation" that Secretary of State Alexander Haig said would be necessary to obtain American support for an Israeli invasion of Lebanon.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Secretary Haig's critics have accused him of "greenlighting" the Israeli Invasion of Lebanon in June 1982.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Haig denies this and says he urged restraint.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The American reaction was that they would not apply any undue pressure on Israel to quit Lebanon as the Israeli presence in Lebanon may prove to be a catalyst for the disparate groups of Lebanon to make common cause against both Syrian and Israeli forces.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Haig's analysis, which Ronald Reagan agreed with, was that this uniting of Lebanese groups would allow President Elias Sarkis to reform the Lebanese central Government and give the Palestinian refugees Lebanese citizenship.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] According to Avi Shlaim, the real driving force behind the Israeli invasion to Lebanon was the defense minister Ariel Sharon.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] One of his aims was the destruction of PLO military infrastructure in Lebanon and undermining it as a political organization, in order to facilitate the absorption of the West Bank by Israel.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The second aim was the establishment of the Maronite government in Lebanon, headed by Bashir Gemayel and signing the peace treaty between two countries, the third aim was the expelling of the Syrian Army from Lebanon.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Also, according to Shlaim, with the completion of Israeli withdrawals from Sinai in March 1982, under the terms of the Egyptian-Israeli Peace Treaty, the Likud-led government of Israel hardened its attitude to the Arab world and became more aggressive.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The military plan with the code name "Big Pines", prepared by IDF, envisaged invasion to Lebanon up to the highway Damascus-Beirut and linking with Maronite forces.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] It was first presented to Israeli cabinet on 20 December 1981 by Begin, but rejected by the majority of ministers.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] On 3 June 1982 Israel's ambassador to the United Kingdom, Shlomo Argov was shot and seriously wounded in London by militants belonging to the Iraqi-backed Abu Nidal militant organization.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The attack was ordered by the Iraqi Intelligence Service.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Following the attack, the assassins drove to the Iraqi embassy in London, where they deposited the weapon.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In his memoirs, Sharon stated that the attack was "merely the spark that lit the fuse".
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israeli prime Minister Begin used this as the "internationally recognized provocation" necessary to invade Lebanon.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The fact that the Abu Nidal organization was the longtime rival of PLO, that its head was condemned to death by the PLO court, and that the British police reported that PLO leaders were on the "hit list" of the attackers did not deter Begin.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] At the Israeli Cabinet meeting the following day, both Begin and Eitan belittled intelligence reports that the likely culprit was the Abu Nidal group.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Begin cut short his own advisor on terrorism, arguing that all Palestinian militants were members of the PLO, while Eitan ridiculed the intelligence staff for splitting hairs and demanded to strike at the PLO.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Yet Abu Nidal had broken with Arafat and PLO in 1974 over a fundamental principle: namely, that the Palestinian national movement would adopt a phased piecemeal approach to secure a Palestinian state and embark on a political path.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The lack of understanding of the difference between Palestinian groups and the total ignorance of Palestinian politics on the part an overwhelming majority of Israelis and Jews played into the hands of those who did not wish to distinguish between the PLO and the Abu Nidal group.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Thus, instead of an initiative to locate the Abu Nidal group in Damascus or Baghdad, the plan to invade Lebanon was activated.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The PLO denied complicity in the attack, but Israel retaliated with punishing air and artillery strikes against Palestinian targets in Lebanon, including the PLO camps.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Sabra and the Shatila refugee camp were bombed for four hours and the local "Gaza" hospital was hit there.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] About 200 people were killed during these attacks.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The PLO hit back firing rockets at northern Israel causing considerable damage and some loss of life.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] According to another source, twenty villages were targeted in Galilee and 3 Israelis were wounded.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] According to Shlaim, Yasser Arafat, at that time being in Saudi Arabia, told the Americans through the Saudis that he was willing to suspend cross-border shelling.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] But that message was disregarded by the Israeli government.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] President Reagan also sent a message to Begin urging him not to widen the attack.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] On 4 June the Israeli cabinet authorized a large scale invasion.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] A Mossad document declassified in 2022 revealed that planning for the invasion began in mid-1981 and that the Lebanese Christian leader Pierre Gemayel was informed of it in January 1982.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] According to the document, Israel's Lebanon policy was mostly dictated by the military rather than the government.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] On 6 June 1982, Israeli forces under direction of Defense Minister Ariel Sharon launched a three-pronged invasion of southern Lebanon in "Operation Peace for Galilee".
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Roughly 60,000 troops and more than 800 tanks, heavily supported by aircraft, attack helicopters, artillery, and missile boats, crossed the Israel–Lebanon border in three areas.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Simultaneously, Israeli armor, paratroopers, and naval commandos set sail in amphibious landing ships from Ashdod towards the Lebanese coast north of Sidon.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israel's publicly stated objective was to push PLO forces back 40 kilometers (25 mi) to the north.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The westernmost Israeli force was to advance up the coastal road to Tyre.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Its mission was to bypass Tyre and destroy three PLO camps in the area, then move up the coast towards Sidon and Damour, while Israeli forces would simultaneously conduct an amphibious landing north of Sidon to cut off the retreat of PLO forces there.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In the center, two divisions were to advance both north and south of the high ground overlooked by Beaufort Castle, which was being used as a PLO stronghold, and take the road junction at Nabatieh, while an elite reconnaissance battalion was to take the castle itself.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The two divisions were then to split, with one heading west to link up with the forces along the coast, and another towards Jezzine and from there along the right flank of Syrian forces in the Bekaa Valley.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The easternmost Israeli force, the largest of the three, advanced into the Bekaa Valley.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Its mission was to prevent Syrian reinforcements from being sent and to stop Syrian forces from attempting to interfere with the operation on the coastal road.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The advance along the coastal road was preceded by heavy artillery bombardment and airstrikes, but quickly became bogged down and was soon behind schedule.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The narrowness of the road forced a slow advance, and Israeli armor became stuck in a large traffic jam.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Several armored vehicles were knocked out by PLO fighters with anti-tank weaponry hiding in three groves along the road.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] One of the lead battalions, which was supposed to bypass Tyre and establish a blocking position to the north of the city, made a wrong turn and found itself in the center of the city, where it was ambushed.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] At eight in the evening the force crossed the Litani River and headed towards Sidon.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In the central sector, the mission went as planned.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The two Israeli divisions bypassed Beaufort Castle on both sides.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Although an order to postpone the capture of Beaufort Castle was issued, it did not reach Israeli forces in time to prevent the operation, and Israeli troops of the Golani Brigade captured the castle in the fiercely-fought Battle of the Beaufort.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The road junction at Nabatieh was also secured by the end of the first day.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Meanwhile, the easternmost force penetrated into the Bekaa Valley and bore down on the Syrian positions.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] One division bypassed Mount Hermon via a road bulldozed by Israeli military engineers and cleared the town of Hasbaiya before swinging right and advancing towards Rachaiya.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Though Israeli forces halted in the floor of the valley, they were flanking Syrian forces from the east and west.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Syrians put up minimal resistance and conducted some harassing artillery fire.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] By the end of the first day, the operation had gone almost entirely according to plan, though the advance along the coastal road was behind schedule.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Despite the delays, the Israeli advance along the coastal road continued steadily.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] This advance was supported by heavy air attacks against PLO positions that included the use of cluster bombs.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israeli missile boats also employed 76mm cannons to destroy targets along the coast, firing 3,500 shells during ten days of fighting.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israeli armor continued to advance towards Sidon, while other Israeli infantry attacked the three Palestinian refugee camps in the area that were used as PLO bases: Rashidiya, Burj ash-Shamali, and al-Bass.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The camps were all crisscrossed with networks of bunkers, trenches, and firing positions.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israelis took each camp section by section using the same method: warnings were blared by loudspeaker urging civilians to leave, before air and artillery bombardment commenced, followed by an infantry assault.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israeli infantry had to engage in fierce urban combat in narrow streets.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The PLO defenders put up strong resistance and sometimes used civilians as human shields.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] It took four days of combat to secure Rashidiya and three days to secure the other two camps.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] At the same time, an Israeli amphibious operation was conducted north of Sidon, beginning with a diversionary bombardment of targets away from the landing zone by missile boats and aircraft.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Two groups of commandos from the Shayetet 13 naval commando unit then came ashore to probe enemy defenses and secure the landing site, one of which swam to the mouth of the Awali River and another which came ashore on the landing beach in rubber dinghies.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] After a brief gunbattle with armed Palestinians, the main landings began, with paratroopers coming ashore in rubber dinghies to establish a beachhead followed by three landing craft that unloaded troops and armor.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Over the following days, the three landing ships moved between Israel and Lebanon, shuttling more troops and armor onto the beachhead.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The PLO response was limited to ineffective mortar fire, while Israeli missile boats and aircraft attacked Palestinian positions in response.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In total, about 2,400 soldiers and 400 tanks and armored personnel carriers were landed.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] From the beach, these forces advanced on Sidon, supported by naval gunfire from missile boats.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] At the same time, Israeli forces in the central sector advanced towards Jezzine while those in the eastern sector remained in place, but began setting up heavy artillery positions that put Syrian SAM units in artillery range.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] After linking up with the forces that had landed north of Sidon, while another force of paratroopers and armor with heavy air and artillery support advanced through central Sidon and cleared a south–north route through the city in fierce fighting.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Another Israeli division passed through the city to link up with the forces north of Sidon.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In the center, most Israeli forces advancing towards Jezzine bypassed the town to continue advancing towards the main highway in the area, leaving a blocking force in the area that was soon joined by an armored brigade.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Fighting broke out in Jezzine between the Israelis and Syrian forces holding the town.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Meanwhile, Israeli forces continued to advance along the Syrians' right flank.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israeli forces advancing along the coast also completed the capture of Sidon.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Paratroopers attacked the Kasbah while a combined force of Golani Brigade infantry and tanks attacked Ain al-Hilweh.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Kasbah was secured in three days; the paratroopers advanced cautiously and managed to take it without suffering any casualties.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] However, the fighting at Ain al-Hilweh was to prove some of the fiercest of the entire war.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The camp was heavily fortified and defended by PLO fighters and Islamic fundamentalists.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The defenders fought fiercely over every alley and house, with civilians who wanted to surrender shot by the fundamentalists.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israeli advance was slow and was supported by massive air and artillery bombardment.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The IDF employed its previous tactics of urging civilians to leave with loudspeakers before attacking an area.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] It took about eight days for the camp to fall, with the battle culminating in a last stand by the defenders at the camp mosque, which was blown up by the IDF.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In an effort to establish air superiority and greater freedom of action, the Israeli Air Force launched Operation Mole Cricket 19 on 9 June.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] During the course of the operation, the Israeli Air Force scored a dramatic victory over the Syrians, shooting down 29 Syrian planes and also destroying 17 Syrian anti-aircraft missile batteries, employing electronic warfare methods to confuse and jam the Syrian radars.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israelis' only known losses were a single UAV shot down and two fighter jets damaged.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Later that night, an Israeli air attack destroyed a Syrian armored brigade moving south from Baalbek, and the IAF attacked and destroyed six more Syrian SAM batteries the following day.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The easternmost Israeli force, which had been stationary, resumed its advance forward up the Bekaa Valley.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In the center, Israeli forces were ambushed by the Syrians as they approached Ain Zhalta, and were pinned down by Syrian forces firing from superior positions.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israelis were bogged down, and an infantry battalion was sent in by helicopter to reinforce them.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The town was only captured after a two-day armored and infantry battle.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The battle cost the Israelis 11 killed and 4 tanks, while the Syrians lost approximately 100 killed and 35 tanks.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] After Ain Zhalta fell, the Israelis advanced to the town of Ain Dara, which overlooked the Beirut-Damascus highway, and captured the heights overlooking the town.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Along the road to Ain Dara, the Israelis encountered Syrian tank and commando units, and found themselves bogged down as the Syrians took advantage of the terrain.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israelis called in air support, and Israeli attack helicopters that took advantage of ravines to fly in low beneath their targets to gain an element of surprise proved particularly effective against Syrian tanks.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] After a daylong battle, the Israelis had surrounded Ain Dara and were in a position to strike on the highway.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] On 10 June 1982, the Israeli air force mistook a column of IDF Nahal Brigade forces for a Syrian commando unit.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] An IAF F-4 Phantom attacked the Battalion 931, advancing in open APCs in south-eastern Lebanon with cluster ammunition.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The unit suffered 24 fatalities and 108 wounded, with a further 30 soldiers shell-shocked.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In the east, Israeli forces advanced along four main routes towards Joub Jannine, along both sides of the Qaraoun reservoir.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Syrian infantrymen armed with anti-tank weapons staged ambushes against Israeli tanks, and Syrian Gazelle helicopters armed with HOT missiles proved effective against Israeli armor.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] However, the Israelis managed to capture the valley floor, and the Syrians retreated.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israelis captured Rachaiya, advanced through Kfar Quoq, and took the outskirts of Yanta.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The extent of Israeli advances ensured that Syrian reinforcements were blocked from deploying west of the Qaraoun reservoir.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] An Israeli armored battalion then probed past Joub Jannine to the town of Sultan Yacoub, and was ambushed by Syrian forces lying in wait.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In the Battle of Sultan Yacoub, the Israelis fought fiercely to extricate themselves, and called in reinforcements and artillery fire to cover the withdrawal.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] After six hours, the Israelis managed to retreat, having lost 10 tanks and 3 armored personnel carriers.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In addition, another major air battle erupted in which the Israeli Air Force shot down 25 Syrian jets and 4 helicopters.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] To the west, as IDF troops mopped up remaining resistance in Tyre and Sidon, the Israeli advance on Beirut continued, and Syrian tank and commando units were then deployed south of Beirut to reinforce the PLO.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] When the Israelis reached the Beirut suburb of Kafr Sill, they met a joint Syrian-PLO force for the first time, and fought a difficult battle to take it.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The IDF temporarily halted its advance in the western sector at Kafr Sill.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] On 11 June, Israel and Syria announced that they had agreed to a cease-fire at noon, which would not include the PLO.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The cease-fire was to come into effect at noon.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Just before the cease-fire was to take effect, the Syrians moved a column of T-72 tanks so as to position it against Israeli forces in the valley.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israeli infantry teams armed with BGM-71 TOW anti-tank missiles ambushed the Syrian column, destroying 11 tanks.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Another air battle also occurred, with the Israelis shooting down 18 more Syrian jets.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israeli advance on Beirut pressed forward in the west, reaching Khalde on 11 June.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Six miles south of Beirut, the town was the last PLO position in front of Beirut Airport.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The PLO fighters, led by Abdullah Siyam, fought a rearguard action which held up the Israeli advance for six days.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israelis, who stood on the outskirts of Beirut, advanced towards the airport, and engaged in frequent combat with PLO and Syrian units as Israeli warplanes continued to bomb PLO positions in Beirut.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The PLO's situation gradually grew worse as the Israeli advance gained ground, threatening to trap the PLO and a Syrian brigade deployed with them in the city.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] On 12 June, the Israeli-Syrian cease-fire was extended to the PLO.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] As the Israeli advance halted, the Israelis turned their attention to the zone they already occupied in southern Lebanon, and began a policy to root out any PLO remnants.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israeli troops began searches for arms caches, and suspected PLO members were systematically rounded up and screened, and taken to a detention camp on the Amoun Heights.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] On 13 June, less than twelve hours after the Israeli-PLO ceasefire had gone into effect, it fell apart, and heavy fighting erupted around Khalde.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] As the fighting raged, an IDF armored unit struck northeast, attempting to bypass Khalde and advance on Baabda, which overlooked the airport and could be used as another staging point to cut the Beirut-Damascus highway.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] By 14 June, Syrian forces were being deployed to Khalde.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Syrian units in Beirut and three commando battalions armed with anti-tank weaponry took up defensive positions southwest of the airport to block any Israeli attempt to capture it.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israelis attempted to flank these defenses by moving off the road past Shuweifat, up a narrow, steep, and winding road towards Baabda, but were ambushed by a Syrian commando battalion.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Syrians attacked Israeli armor with rocket-propelled grenades and anti-tank missiles at close range.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israeli infantry dismounted and engaged the Syrians.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Fierce fighting took place, with the Israelis calling in artillery at very close range to themselves.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israelis advanced relentlessly, and after fourteen hours of fierce combat that raged up through Ain Aanoub and Souq el-Gharb, they broke through the Syrian positions and entered Baabda.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The IDF then immediately sent reinforcements to the column in Baabda to enable it to carry out further operations.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] From Baabda, the Israeli force split into three columns, one of which struck across the highway and entered the mountainous area to the northeast, one swung west and took up positions in the steep hills west of Beirut, and one turned toward Kahale, which was further down the highway.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] To the south, the IDF drove PLO forces out of Shuweifat, but no major battles occurred.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israelis had now cut the Beirut-Damascus highway, cutting off all PLO and Syrian forces in the city.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] On 15 June, Israel offered free passage to all Syrian forces in Beirut if they would withdraw from the city to the Bekaa Valley in the east, but the Syrian government refused and sent further reinforcements to its units along the highway and north of the highway near Beirut.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israelis faced Syrian strongpoints reinforced by armor and artillery all along the highway.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] However, between 16 June and 22 June, the fighting was limited to artillery duels and minor firefights between Israeli and Syrian forces, as both sides reinforced their troops.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] As the two sides prepared for combat, the IDF deemed capturing the Beirut–Damascus highway to be of critical importance.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] On 22 June, the IDF launched an operation to capture the highway.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israeli Air Force flew highly effective missions against Syrian positions and vehicles, with Israeli pilots reporting 130 enemy vehicles destroyed in a single air attack alone.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israeli long-range artillery targeted Syrian strongpoints to the north.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israeli armored forces with artillery support attacked Syrian positions along the highway, with the objective of driving them from the highway all the way back to the edge of the Bekaa Valley.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] With air and artillery support mostly limited to targets north of the highway, the fighting was fierce, especially to the south.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] By the end of the day, Israel accepted an American request for a cease-fire and halted its offensive, but the cease-fire collapsed the following day and the fighting resumed.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] As the Israelis pushed forward, and managed to trap a large Syrian force, Syrian defenses began to collapse.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] For the first time in the war, Syrian troops began to break and run.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] At Aley, which was defended by Iranian volunteers sent to fight for the PLO, the Israelis encountered fierce resistance.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israelis managed to push to the eastern Bekaa Valley, and on 24 June, began to shell the outskirts of Chtaura, which was at the northern mouth of the Bekaa Valley and served as headquarters of all Syrian forces there.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] It was also the last major obstacle before the Syrian border, as well as Syria's capital Damascus itself.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israelis managed to reach the mountain pass near the village of Dahr el-Baidar, which was the last obstacle before Cthaura.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Syrians fought fiercely to hold the pass, and the Israeli advance halted, with the Israelis holding their ground and harassing the Syrians with artillery fire.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] By 25 June, with the remaining Syrian positions on and north of the highway no longer tenable, the Syrians withdrew.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israelis allowed the withdrawal to occur but conducted artillery harassment and continued to shell the outskirts of Chtaura.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Syrians attempted to deploy a SAM battery in the Bekaa Valley at midnight, but Israeli intelligence detected this, and the battery was destroyed in an Israeli air attack.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] By the end of the day, a cease-fire was announced.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israelis stopped at their present positions.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Siege of Beirut had begun on 14 June 1982: Israeli forces had completed the encirclement of the city the previous day.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israelis chose to keep the city under siege rather than forcibly capture it, as they were unwilling to accept the heavy casualties that the heavy street fighting required to capture the city would have resulted in.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israeli forces bombarded targets within Beirut from land, sea, and air, and attempted to assassinate Palestinian leaders through airstrikes.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israeli Navy maintained a blockade on the port of Beirut with a ring of missile boats and patrol boats supported by submarines.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The siege lasted until August, when an agreement was reached in August 1982.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] More than 14,000 PLO combatants evacuated the country in August and September, supervised by the Multinational Force in Lebanon, an international peacekeeping force with troops from the United States, United Kingdom, France, and Italy.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] About 6,500 Fatah fighters relocated from Beirut to Jordan, Syria, Iraq, Sudan, both North and South Yemen, Greece, and Tunisia—the latter of which became the new PLO headquarters.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israel withdrew its forces from west Beirut on 29 September, officially ending Operation Peace for Galilee.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Philip Habib, Ronald Reagan's envoy to Lebanon, provided an understanding (i.e., assurance) to the PLO that the Palestinian civilians in the refugee camps would not be harmed.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] However, increased hostilities against the US resulted in the April 1983 United States Embassy bombing.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In response, the US brokered the May 17 Agreement, in an attempt to stall hostilities between Israel and Lebanon.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] However, this agreement eventually failed to take shape, and hostilities continued.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] These attacks were attributed to Iranian-backed Islamist guerrillas.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Following this incident, international peacekeeping forces were withdrawn from Lebanon.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Following the departure of the PLO and international peacekeepers, Islamist militants began launching guerrilla attacks against Israeli forces.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Suicide bombings were a particularly popular tactic, the most serious being the Tyre headquarters bombings, which twice devastated IDF headquarters in Tyre, and killed 103 Israeli soldiers, border policemen, and Shin Bet agents, as well as 49–56 Lebanese.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The IDF subsequently withdrew from the Shouf Mountains but continued occupying Lebanon south of the Awali River.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] An increased number of Islamic militias began operating in South Lebanon, launching guerrilla attacks on Israeli positions and on pro-Israeli Lebanese militias.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israeli forces often responded with increased security measures and airstrikes on militant positions, and casualties on all sides steadily climbed.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In a vacuum left with eradication of PLO, the disorganized Islamic militants in South Lebanon began to consolidate.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The emerging Hezbollah, soon to become the preeminent Islamic militia, evolved during this period.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] However, scholars disagree as to when Hezbollah came to be regarded as a distinct entity.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Over time, a number of Shi'a group members were slowly assimilated into the organization, such as Islamic Jihad members, Organization of the Oppressed on Earth, and the Revolutionary Justice Organization.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In February 1985, Israel withdrew from Sidon and turned it over to the Lebanese Army, but faced attacks: 15 Israelis were killed and 105 wounded during the withdrawal.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Dozens of pro-Israeli Lebanese militiamen were also assassinated.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] From mid-February to mid-March, the Israelis lost 18 dead and 35 wounded.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] On 11 March, Israeli forces raided the town of Zrariyah, killing 40 Amal fighters and capturing a large stock of arms.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] On 9 April, a Shiite girl drove a car bomb into an IDF convoy, and the following day, a soldier was killed by a land mine.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] During that same period, Israeli forces killed 80 Lebanese guerrillas in five weeks.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Another 1,800 Shi'as were taken as prisoners.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israel withdrew from the Bekaa valley on 24 April, and from Tyre on the 29th.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In June 1985, the IDF unilaterally withdrew to a security zone in southern Lebanon along with its principal Lebanese ally, the South Lebanon Army, completing its troop withdrawal to the security zone on 5 June.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Despite this being considered the end of the war, conflict would continue.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Hezbollah continued to fight the IDF and SLA in the South Lebanon conflict until Israel's final withdrawal from Lebanon in 2000.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] During the course of combat operations, the Israeli Air Force conducted successful ground attack missions against Syrian and PLO targets, with Israeli attack helicopters inflicting heavy losses on Syrian armor.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Israeli jets shot down between 82 and 86 Syrian aircraft in aerial combat, without losses.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] A single Israeli A-4 Skyhawk and two helicopters were shot down by anti-aircraft fire and SAM missiles.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] This was the largest aerial combat battle of the jet age with over 150 fighters from both sides engaged.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Syrian claims of aerial victories were met with skepticism even from their Soviet allies.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The Soviets were so shaken by the staggering losses sustained by their allies that they dispatched the deputy head of their air defense force to Syria to examine how the Israelis had been so dominant.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The Israeli Air Force also performed ground attacks, notably destroying the majority of Syrian anti-aircraft batteries stationed in Lebanon.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] AH-1 Cobra helicopter gunships were employed against Syrian armour and fortifications.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] IAF Cobras destroyed dozens of Syrian Armored fighting vehicles, including some of the modern Soviet T-72 main battle tanks.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The war also witnessed the Israeli Merkava MBT make its first combat debut, facing Syrian T-72 tanks.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] During these engagements, the Israelis claimed that the Merkava proved superior to the T-72, destroying a number of them without sustaining a single loss to T-72 fire.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] However, defense analysts and the Syrians claimed the opposite, saying that their T-72s were highly effective and that none were lost.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The T-72 tanks of the Syrian 2nd Armored Division were credited with not only halting the advance of an Israeli armored brigade on Rashaya on 10 June but pushing them back.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] They tallied the destruction of 33 tanks and the capture of an M60 Patton, which was sent to Damascus and thence transported to Moscow.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Syrian tanks saw similar success against Israeli armor in Ain Zhalta and Sultan Yacoub in fighting on 8–10 June, stemming their advance to capture the Beirut-Damascus highway.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] On 14 September 1982, Bachir Gemayel, the newly elected President of Lebanon, was assassinated by Habib Shartouni of the Syrian Social Nationalist Party.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Israeli forces occupied West Beirut the next day.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] At that time, the Lebanese Christian Militia, also known as the Phalangists, were allied with Israel.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The Israeli command authorized the entrance of a force of approximately 150 Phalangist fighters' into Sabra and the Shatila refugee camp.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Between 460 and 3,500 civilians, mostly Palestinians and Lebanese Shiites were massacred by the Phalangists, who themselves suffered only two casualties.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The Lebanese army's chief prosecutor investigated the killings and counted 460 dead, Israeli intelligence estimated 700–800 dead, and the Palestinian Red Crescent claimed 2,000 dead.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] 1,200 death certificates were issued to anyone who produced three witnesses claiming a family member disappeared during the time of the massacre.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Israeli troops surrounded the camps with tanks and checkpoints, monitoring entrances and exits.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Israeli investigation by the Kahan Commission of Inquiry found that Ariel Sharon bore "personal responsibility" for failing to prevent the massacre, and for failing to act once he learned of the massacre.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The Commission recommended that he be removed as Defense Minister and that he never hold a position in any future Israeli government.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Sharon initially ignored the call to resign, but after the death of an anti-war protester, resigned as Israel's Defense Minister, remaining in Begin's cabinet as a Minister without portfolio.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The 1982 Lebanon War was at first a conventional war up to and including when the PLO were expelled from Beirut.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The war was limited by both Israel and Syria because they were determined to isolate the fighting, not allowing it to turn into an all-out war.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Israeli forces were numerically superior, allowing Israel to maintain both the initiative and an element of surprise.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The Syrian Army fielded six divisions and 500 aircraft, while Israel used five divisions and two brigades, plus 600 aircraft.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] There were numerous other factions involved.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] IDF forces totalled 78,000 men, 1,240 tanks and 1,500 armoured personnel carriers.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] IDF troops were deployed in five divisions and two reinforced brigade-size units.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The IDF maintained additional forces on the Golan Heights as an area reserve.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The Syrian Army had over 30,000 troops deployed in Lebanon in June 1982.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The largest concentration was in the Bekaa Valley where the 1st Armoured Division consisting of the 58th Mechanised and the 76th and 91st Armoured Brigades.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The 62nd Independent Armored Brigade and ten commando battalions were also assigned to the division.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Syria deployed around 400 tanks in the Bekaa Valley.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] 19 surface-to-air missile batteries, including SA6's, were also deployed in the Bekaa Valley.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] In Beirut and the Shouf Mountains were the 85th Infantry Brigade, the PLA, As-Sa'iqa and 20 commando battalions.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Syria deployed around 200 tanks in this area.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Their primary mission was to protect the Beirut-Damascus Highway, which was Syria's primary supply line in the region.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Palestinian Liberation Organization forces continued to grow in Lebanon, with full-time military personnel numbering around 15,000 fedayeen, although only 6,000 of these – including 4,500 regulars – deployed in the south.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] They were armed with 80 aging tanks, many of them no longer mobile, and with 100 to 200 pieces of artillery.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] According to Israeli analysts Schiff and Ya'ari (1984), the PLO more than quadrupled its artillery from 80 cannons and rocket launchers in July 1981 to 250 in June 1982.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] PLO primary forces consisted of three conventional brigades – each of 2,000 to 2,500 men – and of seven artillery battalions.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Each brigade comprised contingents of the many PLO factions.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The Yarmouk Brigade was stationed along the coastal strip while the Kastel Brigade was in the south.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The Karameh Brigade was stationed on the eastern slopes of Mount Hermon in the area called Fatahland.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Heavy weapons consisted of about 60 T-34, T-54 and T-55 tanks (most of them dug in as pillboxes), up to 250 130mm and 155 mm artillery, many BM21 Katyusha multiple-rocket launchers plus heavy mortars.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Palestinian groups of the radical Rejectionist Front joined forces with the mainstream PLO.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Left wing parties joined forces with the PLO in what came to be known as the "joint forces".
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The first UNIFIL troops were deployed in the area on 23 March 1978.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] These troops were reassigned from other UN peacekeeping operations in the area, namely the United Nations Emergency Force and the United Nations Disengagement Observer Force Zone.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] During the 1982 Lebanon War, UN positions were overrun, primarily by the South Lebanon Army forces under Saad Haddad.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Estimates of numbers of the casualties in the conflict vary widely.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] By the end of the first week, 14 June 1982, International Red Cross and Lebanese police figures said that 9,583 had died and 16,608 injured.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] By the end of the second week, they said up to 14,000 people died and 20,000 were injured, mostly civilians.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] During the Siege of Beirut, by late August 1982, Lebanese sources put the death toll in Beirut at 6,776.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] This figure included victims of the 4 June 1982, bombing, which occurred two days before the operation officially started.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Lebanese police and international doctors serving in Beirut put the number of civilian casualties at about 80%.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] According to American military analyst Richard Gabriel, all factions in the conflicts agree that between 4,000 and 5,000 civilians died during the siege caused by military activity of all sides.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] He states that most of the observers that were present on the ground and other relevant sources in Lebanon agree that estimates of 8,000–10,000 are too high.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Accurate numbers of total casualties are hard to estimate, due to "[t]he chaos of warfare, the destruction of city neighborhoods and refugee camps, the haste with which bodies were buried in mass graves and the absence of impartial agencies".
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Many officials in Beirut, including those of the International Red Cross, claimed that the number of deaths were extremely difficult to estimate correctly.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] At least one official from a relief organization claimed that in the South about 80% of deaths were civilian and only 20% military.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] In early September 1982, the independent Beirut newspaper *An Nahar* published an estimate of deaths from hospital and police records covering the period from 6 June to 31 August 1982.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] It claimed that 17,285 people were killed: 5,515 people, both military and civilian, in the Beirut area; and 2,513 civilians, as well as 9,797 military forces, including PLO and Syrians, outside of the Beirut area.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The Lebanese authorities gave a figure of 19,085 killed and 30,000 wounded; in Beirut alone 6,775 died, 84% of them civilians.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] In southern Lebanon, around 20% of those dead were civilians.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] They do not include the estimated 800–3,500 killed in the Sabra and Shatila massacre.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Richard Gabriel estimated that roughly 2,400 PLO fighters were killed during the war, of whom about 1,400 were killed throughout southern Lebanon and another 1,000 killed during the Siege of Beirut.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Gabriel also estimated that between 5,000 and 8,000 civilians died during the war.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Some later estimates have put the total figure at 18–19,000 killed and more than 30,000 wounded, most of them civilians.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] 80% of villages in South Lebanon were damaged, with some completely destroyed.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The Israeli government maintained that about 1,000 Palestinian fighters and 800 Lebanese civilians died during the invasion, excluding the siege of Beirut.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Anthony Tucker-Jones estimated that about 1,500 PLO fighters were killed.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Kenneth Pollack estimated that 1,200 Syrian soldiers were killed and about 3,000 wounded during the war.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] According to Israeli figures, Israeli losses in Operation Peace for Galilee were 368 dead and 2,383 wounded, from 6 June until 10 October.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The highest ranking IDF casualty of the war was Brigadier General Yekutiel Adam, who was Deputy Chief of Staff of the IDF and had been appointed to be the next Director-General of the Mossad.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] He was killed by a Palestinian fighter while seeking protection in a house in Dawha, near Damour, during a mortar attack.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Other Israeli fatalities included one Colonel, two Lieutenant Colonels; 19 Majors, 28 Captains, 46 Lieutenants, 132 Sergeants, 90 Corporals, and 49 Privates.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] According to Kenneth Pollack, Israeli losses in action against the Syrians were 195 dead and 872 wounded.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] 130 Israeli tanks were destroyed or damaged by the Syrians, as were 175 APCs.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The IDF also listed six soldiers as Missing in action in the Battle of Sultan Yacoub.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Two prisoners and the bodies of another two were later returned to Israel but two soldiers remain missing.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Palestinian factions captured 11 IDF soldiers during the war, including one of the soldiers missing from Sultan Yacoub, an Israeli Air Force pilot in the Beaufort battle, a soldier during the Siege of Beirut and eight soldiers in the raid on an IDF observation post in Bhamdoun.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] All eleven prisoners were subsequently released in prisoner exchanges.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The IDF's total casualties in Lebanon from the start of Operation Peace for Galilee in June 1982 to the withdrawal to the security zone in June 1985 amounted 654 killed and 3,887 wounded.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The IDF continued to occupy a substantial part of Lebanon even after the withdrawal to security zone in June 1985.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Resistance continued and IDF losses continued to mount.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] By the time IDF withdrew from Lebanon in May 2000 the total number of IDF fatalities had reached 1,216 killed since June 1982.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Israeli civilian casualties from cross-border shelling numbered 9–10 killed and at least 248 wounded between June 1982 and 1999.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] In September 1982, the PLO withdrew most of its forces from Lebanon.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] With U.S. assistance, Israel and Lebanon reached an accord in May 1983, that set the stage to withdraw Israeli forces from Lebanon while letting them patrol a "security zone" together with the Lebanese Army.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The instruments of ratification were never exchanged, and in March 1984, under pressure from Syria, Lebanon cancelled the agreement.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] In January 1985, Israel started to withdraw most of its troops, leaving a small residual Israeli force and an Israeli-supported militia, the South Lebanon Army in southern Lebanon in a "security zone", which Israel considered a necessary buffer against attacks on its northern territory.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The Israeli withdrawal to the security zone ended in June 1985.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Israel withdrew fully from Lebanon in 2000.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The political vacuum resulting from the 1985 Israeli withdrawal would eventually lead to the *de facto* Syrian occupation of Lebanon.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Syria would gain much more power over Lebanon than what it enjoyed before 1982, but it would no longer align with the PLO.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] In the War of the Camps that followed the Israeli withdrawal, Syria fought their former Palestinian allies.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Following Arafat's decision of June 1982, by September 1982, the PLO had withdrawn most of its forces from West Beirut.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Syria backed the anti-Arafat PLO forces of Abu Musa in the Beka valley from May 1983.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] When Arafat castigated the Syrian government for blocking PLO supplies in June 1983, the Syrian government declared Arafat a *persona non-grata* on 24 June 1983.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] With the withdrawal of the PLO leadership from Tripoli in December 1983 there was an Egyptian-PLO rapprochement, this was found to be encouraging by the Reagan administration but was condemned by the Israeli government.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Ariel Sharon requested permission for a military operation that would only go 25 miles into Lebanon, and would only be for 2–3 days.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] On this basis, nearly the entire Knesset voted in favor of going to war.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Only Hadash opposed the war, and even submitted a no-confidence motion against the Israeli government.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Hadash Knesset member Meir Vilner said in the Knesset plenary session that: "The government is leading Israel to an abyss.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] It is doing something that in the course of time might lead to crying for generations".
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] In response, they were condemned, and calls were heard, among others from the editor of Yediot Ahronoth, to prosecute them for treason.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Left-wing Knesset members, including Shulamit Aloni and Yossi Sarid, were absent from the plenary for the vote.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Even the Labor faction voted in support.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] By mid January 1983 Rabin was saying that the Israeli attempt to impose a peace agreement on Lebanon by the use of force was a "mistake" based upon an "illusion".
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Heavy Israeli casualties, alleged disinformation of Israeli government leaders and the Israeli public by Israeli military, as well as political advocates of the campaign and lack of clear goals led to increasing disquiet among Israelis.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] This culminated in a large protest rally in Tel Aviv on 25 September 1982, organized by the Peace Now movement, following the 1982 Sabra and Shatila massacre.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Organizers claimed 400,000 people participated in the rally, and it became known as the "400,000 rally".
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Other estimates put the figure much lower, maybe reaching 100,000 Israelis but including thousands of reserve soldiers back from Lebanon.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The Israeli-Maronite alliance dissolved, and Sharon's goal of installing a pro-Israel Christian government in Beirut was not accomplished.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] 850,000 Christians emigrated out of Lebanon during the Civil War, most of them permanently.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] This heavily impacted the civilian population from both sides, with more than 5,000 killed from both sides.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The Mountain War ended after the Christian forces and civilians withdrew to the town of Deir el Kamar, where they were besieged for 3 months before all hostilities ceased and they were transported to East Beirut.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The invasion led to the switching of sides of Amal Movement, which used to fight against the PLO prior to the invasion.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The invasion is also popularly held to be the major catalyst for the creation of the Iranian and Syrian supported Hezbollah organization, which by 1991 was the sole armed militia in Lebanon not supported by Israel and by 2000 had completely replaced the vanquished PLO in Southern Lebanon.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] According to Abraham Rabinovich, the complete dominance of U.S. and Israeli technology and tactics over those of the Eastern Bloc was a factor that hastened the demise of the Warsaw Pact and the Soviet Union.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] However, this was not the first confrontation in which Soviet weaponry had been outmatched by American weaponry.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] In many of the Cold War conflicts the Americans and their allies had superior technology.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Nonetheless, the gap between the First World and Second World weaponry was more apparent in the 1980s and weighed more heavily on Second World leaders.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] One of the lingering consequences of the Israeli invasion of Lebanon was the creation of Hezbollah.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] In 2000, when Ehud Barak was Israeli Prime Minister, Israel withdrew from the security zone to behind the Blue Line.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Lebanon and Hezbollah continue to claim a small area called Shebaa Farms as Lebanese territory, but Israel insists that it is captured Syrian territory with the same status as the Golan Heights.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The United Nations has not determined the final status of Shebaa Farms but has determined that Israel has complied with UNSC resolution 425.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The UN Secretary-General had concluded that, as of 16 June 2000, Israel had withdrawn its forces from Lebanon in accordance with UN Security Council Resolution 425 of 1978, bringing closure to the 1982 invasion as far as the UN was concerned.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Israel's withdrawal from Lebanon led to pressure on the Syrians to withdraw their occupation forces and this pressure intensified after the assassination of the popular Lebanese Prime Minister, Rafik Hariri.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] On 26 April 2005 the Syrian occupation forces withdrew from Lebanon.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] On 16 December 1982, the United Nations General Assembly condemned the Sabra and Shatila massacre and declared it to be an act of genocide.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The voting record on section D of Resolution 37/123, which "resolves that the massacre was an act of genocide", was: yes: 123; no: 0; abstentions: 22; non-voting: 12.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The abstentions were: Belgium, Denmark, France, Germany (Federal Republic), Iceland, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Norway, Portugal, Sweden, United Kingdom, U.S., Canada, Australia, New Zealand, Israel, Ivory Coast, Papua New Guinea, Barbados and Dominican Republic.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Some delegates disputed the claim that the massacre constituted genocide.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] In 1982, an international commission investigated into reported violations of International Law by Israel during its invasion of the Lebanon.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Chairman was Seán MacBride, the other members were Richard A.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Falk, Kader Asmal, Brian Bercusson, Géraud de la Pradelle, and Stefan Wild.
[src:maritime-history/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Following a four-month investigation, on 8 February 1983, the Kahan Commission submitted its report, which was released to the public by spokesman Bezalel Gordon simultaneously in Hebrew and English.
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] The rank of lieutenant has different meanings in different military formations, but in most forces it is sub-divided into a senior (first lieutenant) and junior (second lieutenant) rank.
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] In navies, while certain rank insignia may carry the name lieutenant, the term may also be used to relate to a particular post or duty, rather than a rank.
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] In Indonesia, "first lieutenant" is known as *Letnan Satu* (*Lettu*), Indonesian National Armed Forces uses this rank across all three of its services.
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] It is just above the rank of second lieutenant and just below the rank of captain.
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] In the Israel Defense Forces, the rank above second lieutenant is simply lieutenant (Segen).
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] In the British Army and Royal Marines, the rank above second lieutenant is simply lieutenant (pronounced *lef-tenant*), with no ordinal attached.
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] Before 1871, when the whole British Army switched to using the current rank of "lieutenant", the Royal Artillery, Royal Engineers and fusilier regiments used "first lieutenant" and "second lieutenant".
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] The *first lieutenant* (often abbreviated "1st Lt") in a Royal Navy ship is a post or appointment, rather than a rank.
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] Historically the lieutenants in a ship were ranked in accordance with seniority, with the most senior being termed the first lieutenant and acting as the second-in-command, unless the ship was complemented with a commander.
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] Although lieutenants are no longer ranked by seniority, the post of "first lieutenant" remains.
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] The post of *first lieutenant* in a shore establishment carries a similar responsibility to the *first lieutenant* of a capital ship.
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] Colloquial terms in the Royal Navy for the *first lieutenant* include "number one", "the jimmy" (or "jimmy the one") and "James the First" (a back-formation referring to James I of England).
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] The first lieutenant may hold the rank of sub-lieutenant, lieutenant or lieutenant-commander.
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] Space Force, a first lieutenant is a junior commissioned officer.
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] It is equivalent to the rank of lieutenant (junior grade) in the other uniformed services.
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] Promotion to first lieutenant is governed by Department of Defense policies derived from the Defense Officer Personnel Management Act of 1980.
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] DOPMA guidelines suggest all "fully qualified" officers should be promoted to first lieutenant.
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] A second lieutenant (grade O-1) is usually promoted to first lieutenant (grade O-2) after 18 months in the Army or 24 months in the Marine Corps and Air & Space Forces.
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] The difference between the two ranks is slight, primarily being experience and a higher pay grade.
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] It is not uncommon to see officers moved to positions requiring more experience after promotion to first lieutenant.
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] For example, in the Army and Marine Corps these positions can include leading a specialty platoon, or assignment as the executive officer for a company-sized unit (70–250 soldiers or marines).
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] Coast Guard, "first lieutenant" is the name of a billet and position title, rather than rank.
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] Officers aboard early sailing ships were the captain and a number of lieutenants.
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] The senior among those lieutenants was known as the first lieutenant, and would have assumed command if the captain were absent or incapacitated.
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] As modern ships have become more complex, requiring specialized knowledge of engineering, communications, and weapons, the "first lieutenant" is the officer in command of the deck department responsible for line handling during mooring and underway replenishment.
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] On smaller ships, the officer of the "first lieutenant" billet holds the rank of lieutenant, junior grade or ensign.
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] On larger vessels, the position of "first lieutenant" is held by a lieutenant or, in the case of extremely large warships such as cruisers or aircraft carriers, the position of "first lieutenant" may be held by a lieutenant commander or even commander.
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] However, on submarines and in aircraft squadrons, where the deck department may only have a few junior sailors, the "first lieutenant" billet may be filled by a first-class petty officer or chief petty officer.
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] Navy as the "first lieutenant division" is usually composed of junior sailors (E-3 and below) who are completing their ninety days of temporary assigned duty, or TAD, that all enlisted personnel are required to perform when initially assigned to a command.
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] The primary mission of the division is servicing, cleaning, organizing and inventorying items within a command.
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] The term "first lieutenant" had a dual meaning in the United States Revenue Cutter Service (known until 1894 as the United States Revenue-Marine).
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] The position title of first lieutenant was held by a junior officer who was in charge of deck operations and gunnery.
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] The rank of first lieutenant was the equivalent of lieutenant in the current rank structure of the U.S.
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] Navy, United States Public Health Service Commissioned Corps, and National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration Commissioned Officer Corps.
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] The next senior officer ranking above first lieutenant was captain and the next two lower officer ranks were second and third lieutenant, respectively.
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] When the Revenue Cutter Service merged with the United States Life-Saving Service to form the U.S.
[src:maritime-history/1st-lieutenant] Coast Guard in 1915, the rank of first lieutenant carried over into Coast Guard and remained in use until 1918, when the Coast Guard adopted the rank structure of the U.S.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] The **2006 Lebanon War** was a 34-day armed conflict in Lebanon, fought between Hezbollah and Israel.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] The war started on 12 July 2006 and continued until a United Nations-brokered ceasefire went into effect in the morning on 14 August 2006, though it formally ended on 8 September 2006 when Israel lifted its naval blockade of Lebanon.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] It marked the third Israeli invasion into Lebanon since 1978.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] After Israel's withdrawal from southern Lebanon in 2000, Hezbollah aimed for the release of Lebanese citizens held in Israeli prisons.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] On 12 July 2006, Hezbollah ambushed Israeli soldiers on the border, killing three and capturing two; a further five were killed during a failed Israeli rescue attempt.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Hezbollah demanded an exchange of prisoners with Israel.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Israel launched airstrikes and artillery fire on targets in Lebanon, attacking both Hezbollah military targets and Lebanese civilian infrastructure, including Beirut's Rafic Hariri International Airport.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Israel launched a ground invasion of Southern Lebanon and imposed an air-and-naval blockade on the country.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Hezbollah then launched more rockets into northern Israel and engaged the IDF in guerrilla warfare from hardened positions.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] According to Israeli sources, Hezbollah fired close to 4,000 rockets and missiles at Israel from their arsenal of around 15,000 held before the war.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] The Lebanese Army began deploying in Southern Lebanon on 17 August and the blockade was lifted on 8 September.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] On 1 October, most Israeli troops withdrew from Lebanon, although the last of the troops continued to occupy the border-straddling village of Ghajar.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Both Hezbollah and the Israeli government claimed victory, while the Winograd Commission deemed the war a missed opportunity for Israel as it did not lead to disarmament of Hezbollah.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] The conflict is believed to have killed between 1,191 and 1,300 Lebanese people, and 165 Israelis.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] It severely damaged Lebanese civil infrastructure, and displaced approximately one million Lebanese and 300,000–500,000 Israelis.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] The remains of the two captured soldiers, whose fates were unknown, were returned to Israel on 16 July 2008 as part of a prisoner exchange.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] The war is known in Lebanon as the **July War** (Arabic: حرب تموز, *Ḥarb Tammūz*) and in Israel as the **Second Lebanon War** (Hebrew: מלחמת לבנון השנייה, *Milhemet Levanon HaShniya*).
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] The war is also known as the **Israel–Hezbollah War of 2006**.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Starting about this time, increasing demographic tensions related to the Lebanese National Pact, which had divided governmental powers among religious groups throughout the country 30 years previously, began running high and led in part to the Lebanese Civil War (1975–1990).
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] During the 1978 Israeli invasion of southern Lebanon, Israel failed to stem the Palestinian attacks.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Israel invaded Lebanon again in 1982 and forcibly expelled the PLO.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Israel withdrew to a borderland buffer zone in southern Lebanon, held with the aid of proxy militants in the South Lebanon Army (SLA).
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] The invasion also led to the conception of a new Shi'a militant group, which in 1985, established itself politically under the name Hezbollah, and declared an armed struggle to end the Israeli occupation of Lebanese territory.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] When the Lebanese Civil War ended and other warring factions agreed to disarm, both Hezbollah and the SLA refused.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Ten years later, Israel withdrew from South Lebanon to the UN-designated and internationally recognized Blue Line border in 2000.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] The withdrawal also led to the immediate collapse of the SLA, and Hezbollah quickly took control of the area.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] In 2005, Syrian forces withdrew from Lebanon.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] In August 2006, in an article in *The New Yorker*, Seymour Hersh claimed that the White House gave the green light for the Israeli government to execute an attack on Hezbollah in Lebanon.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Supposedly, communication between the Israeli government and the US government about this came as early as two months in advance of the capture of two Israeli soldiers and the killing of eight others by Hezbollah prior to the conflict in July 2006.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] In June 2005, an Israel Defense Forces (IDF) paratroop unit operating near the Shebaa Farms engaged three Lebanese it identified as Hezbollah special force members, killing one.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Videotapes recovered by the paratroopers contained footage of the three recording detailed accounts of the area.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Over the following 12 months, Hezbollah made three unsuccessful attempts to abduct Israeli soldiers.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] On 21 November 2005, a number of Hezbollah special forces attempted to attack an Israeli outpost in Ghajar, a village straddling the border between Lebanon and the Golan Heights.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] The outpost had been deserted following an intelligence warning, and three of the Hezbollah militants were killed when Israeli sniper David Markovich shot a rocket-propelled grenade they were carrying, causing it to explode.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] From his sniper position, Markovich shot and killed a fourth gunman shortly thereafter.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] At around 9 am local time on 12 July 2006, Hezbollah launched diversionary rocket attacks toward Israeli military positions near the coast and near the border village of Zar'it as well as on the Israeli town of Shlomi and other villages.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Six Israeli military positions were fired on, and the surveillance cameras knocked out.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] At the same time, a Hezbollah ground contingent infiltrated the border into Israel through a "dead zone" in the border fence, hiding in an overgrown wadi.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] They attacked a patrol of two Israeli Humvees patrolling the border near Zar'it, using pre-positioned explosives and anti-tank missiles, killing three soldiers, injuring two, and capturing two soldiers (First Sergeant Ehud Goldwasser and Sergeant First Class Eldad Regev).
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] In response to the Hezbollah feint attacks, the IDF conducted a routine check of its positions and patrols, and found that contact with two jeeps was lost.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] A rescue force was immediately dispatched to the area, and confirmed that two soldiers were missing after 20 minutes.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] A Merkava Mk III tank, an armored personnel carrier, and a helicopter were immediately dispatched into Lebanon.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] The tank hit a large land mine, killing its crew of four.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Another soldier was killed and two lightly injured by mortar fire as they attempted to recover the bodies.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Nasrallah claimed that Israel had broken a previous deal to release these prisoners, and since diplomacy had failed, violence was the only remaining option.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Nasrallah declared that "no military operation will result in rescuing these prisoners...
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] The only method, as I indicated, is that of indirect negotiations and a swap [of prisoners]".
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Hezbollah had two ministers serving in the Lebanese cabinet at that time.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] In response, Lebanese Prime Minister Fouad Siniora denied any knowledge of the raid and stated that he did not condone it.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] An emergency meeting of the Lebanese government reaffirmed this position.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] The Israel Defense Forces attacked targets within Lebanon with artillery and airstrikes hours before the Israeli Cabinet met to discuss a response.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] The targets consisted of bridges and roads in Lebanon, which were hit to prevent Hezbollah from transporting the abductees.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] An Israeli airstrike also destroyed the runways of Beirut–Rafic Hariri International Airport.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] The Israeli Air Force also targeted Hezbollah's long-range rocket-and-missile stockpiles, destroying many of them on the ground in the first days of the war.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Many of Hezbollah's longer-range rocket launchers were destroyed within the first hours of the Israeli attack.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Later that same day (12 July 2006), the Cabinet decided to authorize the Prime Minister, the Defense Minister and their deputies to pursue the plan which they had proposed for action within Lebanon.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Prime Minister Olmert officially demanded that the Israel Defense Forces avoid civilian casualties whenever possible.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Israel's chief of staff Dan Halutz said, "if the soldiers are not returned, we will turn Lebanon's clock back 20 years" while the head of Israel's Northern Command Udi Adam said, "this affair is between Israel and the state of Lebanon.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] On 12 July 2006, the Israeli Cabinet promised that Israel would "respond aggressively and harshly to those who carried out, and are responsible for, today's action".
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] On 16 July, the Israeli Cabinet released a communiqué explaining that, although Israel had engaged in military operations *within* Lebanon, its war was not against the Lebanese government.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] When asked in August about the proportionality of the response, Prime Minister Olmert stated that the "war started not only by killing eight Israeli soldiers and abducting two but by shooting Katyusha and other rockets on the northern cities of Israel on that same morning.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] During the first day of the war the Israeli Air Force, artillery and navy conducted more than 100 attacks mainly against Hezbollah bases in south Lebanon, among them the regional headquarters in Yatar.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Five bridges across the Litani and Zahrani rivers were also destroyed, reportedly to prevent Hezbollah from transferring the abducted soldiers to the north.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Attacks from land, sea and air continued in the following days.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Among the targets hit were the Hezbollah headquarters in the southern suburbs of Beirut as well as the offices and homes of the leadership, the compounds of al-Manar TV station and al-Nour radio station, and the runways and fuel depots of the Rafic Hariri International Airport in Beirut.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Also targeted were Hezbollah bases, weapons depots and outposts as well as bridges, roads and petrol stations in south Lebanon.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Forty-four civilians were killed throughout the day.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] It was later reported that the Israel Air Force after midnight, 13 July, attacked and destroyed 59 stationary medium-range Fajr rocket launchers positioned throughout southern Lebanon.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Operation Density allegedly only took 34 minutes to carry out but was the result of six years of intelligence gathering and planning.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Between half and two-thirds of Hezbollah medium-range rocket capability was estimated by the IDF to have been wiped out.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] According to Israeli journalists Amos Harel and Avi Issacharoff the operation was "Israel's most impressive military action" and a "devastating blow for Hezbollah".
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] In the coming days IAF allegedly also attacked and destroyed a large proportion of Hezbollah's long range Zelzal-2 missiles.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] American officials claimed that the Israelis overstated the effectiveness of the air war against Hezbollah and cited the failure to hit any of the Hezbollah leaders in spite of dropping twenty-three tons of high explosives in a single raid on the Beirut Southern suburbs of Dahiya.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] The Israeli assessments are "too large," said one US official.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Al-Manar TV station only went dark for two minutes after the strike before it was back into the air.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] The TV station was bombed 15 times during the war but never faltered after the first hiccup.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] According to military analyst William Arkin there is "little evidence" that the Israeli Air Force even attempted, much less succeeded in, wiping out the medium- and long-range-rocket capability in the first days of the war.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] He dismissed the whole claim as an "absurdity" and a "tale".
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Benjamin Lambeth, however, insisted that it was far-fetched to suggest that the "authoritative Israeli leadership pronouncements" were not based on facts.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] He admitted however that there was "persistent uncertainty" surrounding the "few known facts and figures" concerning the alleged attacks.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] During the war the Israeli Air Force flew 11,897 combat missions, which was more than the number of sorties during the 1973 October War (11,223) and almost double the number during the 1982 Lebanon War (6,052).
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] The Israeli artillery fired 170,000 shells, more than twice the number fired in the 1973 October War.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] A senior officer in the IDF Armored Corps told *Haaretz* that he would be surprised if it turned out that even five Hezbollah fighters had been killed by the 170,000 shells fired.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] The combined effect of the massive air and artillery bombardment on Hezbollah capacity to fire short-range Katyusha rockets on northern Israel was very meager.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] According to the findings of the post-war military investigations the IDF shelling succeeded only in destroying about 100 out of 12,000 Katyusha launchers.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] The massive fire led to a severe shortage of ammunition towards the end of the war.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Northern command had prepared a list before the war on potential Hezbollah targets, identified by the Israeli intelligence, to be struck in case of renewed hostilities.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] By the fourth day of the war the IDF ran out of targets, as all the 83 targets on the list had already been hit.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] A high-ranking IDF officer told reporters off the record that the Israeli chief of staff Dan Halutz had ordered the air force to destroy ten 12-story buildings in the Southern suburbs of Beirut for every rocket that fell on Haifa.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] The statement was denied by the IDF spokesperson.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] On 16 July, eight employees of the Israel Railways were killed by direct rocket hits on the Haifa train depot.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Hezbollah leader Hassan Nasrallah defended the attacks, saying that Hezbollah initially had aimed its rockets on "military sites only".
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] But since Israel, he said, had systematically bombed civilian targets he felt that Hezbollah had no choice but to answer in kind and target Israeli cities.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] The attack on the Haifa depot was not the first civilian target to be hit by Hezbollah.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Civilians in the border communities were hurt in the initial cover fire on IDF positions for the cross-border raid.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Two Israeli civilians were killed in an attack near the air force base at Mount Meron on 14 July.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Since Hezbollah rockets were not very accurate it is unclear whether civilians were intentionally targeted in these attacks.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] After the attack on Haifa, however, Hezbollah made no attempt to cover this fact.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] According to a Human Rights Watch study civilian Israeli targets were mentioned four times as often in official Hezbollah war time communiques as was military targets.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Hezbollah TV station al-Manar warned both in Arabic and Hebrew specific Israeli communities for future rocket attacks.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Similarly Hezbollah sent text messages to warn Israeli residents to evacuate their homes to avoid being targeted by rocket attacks.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Israel published an alleged range card for upgraded Grad rocket launcher placed outside the village of Shihin in the Western sector of South Lebanon, issued by the Artillery Department of the elite Nasr Unit of Hezbollah.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] This list included 91 targets, 56 of whom were civilian and 27 were IDF posts or bases.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] The military targets had three-digit reference numbers while civilian targets had double-digit numbers.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] During the war, the Hezbollah rocket force fired between 3,970 and 4,228 rockets at a rate of more than 100 per day, unprecedented since the Iran–Iraq War.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] About 95% of these were 122 mm (4.8 in) Katyusha artillery rockets, which carried warheads up to 30 kg (66 lb) and had a range of up to 30 km (19 mi).
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] An estimated 23% of these rockets hit cities and built-up areas across northern Israel, while the remainder hit open areas.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Cities hit were Haifa, Hadera, Nazareth, Tiberias, Nahariya, Safed, Shaghur, Afula, Kiryat Shmona, Beit She'an, Karmiel, Acre, and Ma'alot-Tarshiha, as well as dozens of towns, kibbutzim, moshavim, and Druze and Israeli-Arab villages.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Israeli Defense Minister Amir Peretz ordered commanders to prepare civil defense plans.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] One million Israelis had to stay near or in bomb shelters or security rooms, with some 250,000 civilians evacuating the north and relocating to other areas of the country.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] After the high number of Lebanese civilian casualties in the Qana airstrike, Israel announced a unilateral freeze in its air attacks on Lebanon.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Hezbollah then halted its own rocket attacks on Israel.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] When Israel resumed its air attacks on Lebanon, Hezbollah followed suit and recommenced rocket attacks on Israeli targets.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Hezbollah rocket attacks also targeted and succeeded in hitting military targets in Israel.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] The Israeli military censorship was, however, very strict and explicitly forbade Israel-based media from reporting such incidents.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Initially Israel did not confirm that the victims were military but eventually relented.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] On 6 August, two elderly Arab women in Haifa were killed, and an Arab man was mortally wounded, by Hezbollah rocket fire.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] The day after Hezbollah leader Nasrallah appealed to Haifa's Arab community to leave the city so as not be hurt.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] After the initial Israeli response, Hezbollah declared an all-out military alert.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Hezbollah was estimated to have 13,000 missiles at the beginning of the conflict.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Israeli newspaper *Haaretz* described Hezbollah as a trained, skilled, well-organized, and highly motivated infantry that was equipped with the cream of modern weaponry from the arsenals of Syria, Iran, Russia, and China.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Hezbollah's satellite TV station Al-Manar reported that the attacks had included a Fajr-3 and a Ra'ad 1, both liquid-fuel missiles developed by Iran.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Hezbollah engaged in guerrilla warfare with IDF ground forces, fighting from well-fortified positions, often in urban areas, and attacking with small, well-armed units.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Hezbollah fighters were highly trained, and were equipped with flak jackets, night-vision goggles, communications equipment, and sometimes with Israeli uniforms and equipment.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] An Israeli soldier who participated in the war said that Hezbollah fighters were "nothing like Hamas or the Palestinians.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] During engagements with the IDF, Hezbollah concentrated on inflicting losses on the IDF, believing an unwillingness to absorb steady losses to be Israel's strategic weakness.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Hezbollah countered IDF armor through the use of sophisticated Iranian-made anti-tank guided missiles (ATGMs).
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] According to Merkava tank program administration, 52 Merkava main battle tanks were damaged (45 of them by different kinds of ATGM), missiles penetrated 22 tanks, but only 5 tanks were destroyed, one of them by an improvised explosive device (IED).
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] The Merkava tanks that were penetrated were predominantly Mark II and Mark III models, but five Mark IVs were also penetrated.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] All but two of these tanks were rebuilt and returned to service.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] The IDF declared itself satisfied with the Merkava Mark IV's performance during the war.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Hezbollah caused additional casualties using ATGMs to collapse buildings onto Israeli troops sheltering inside.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] As a result, IDF units did not linger in any one area for an extended period of time.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Hezbollah fighters often used tunnels to emerge quickly, fire an anti-tank missile, and then disappear again.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] On 19 July a force from the Maglan special forces unit seized a fortified Hezbollah dugout adjacent to the Shaked post; two IDF soldiers and five Hezbollah operatives were killed in the battle.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] In interviews, Lebanese President Emile Lahoud criticized Israel's attacks and was supportive of Hezbollah, noting Hezbollah's role in ending Israel's previous occupation of southern Lebanon.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] On 12 July 2006, PBS interviewed the Lebanese ambassador Farid Abboud to the United States and his Israeli counterpart.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] The interview discussed Hezbollah's connection to the Lebanese government.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Israel never declared war on Lebanon, and said it only attacked Lebanese governmental institutions which it suspected of being used by Hezbollah.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] The Lebanese government played a role in shaping the conflict.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] On 14 July 2006, the office of Lebanese Prime Minister Fouad Siniora issued a statement that called on US President George W.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Bush to exert all his efforts on Israel to stop its attacks in Lebanon and reach a comprehensive ceasefire.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] A US–French draft resolution that was influenced by the Lebanese Siniora Plan and which contained provisions for Israeli withdrawal, military actions, and mutual prisoner release was rejected by the US and Israel.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Many Lebanese accused the US government of stalling the ceasefire resolution and of support of Israel's attacks.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] In a poll conducted two weeks into the conflict, only 8% of the respondents felt that the US would support Lebanon, while 87% supported Hezbollah's fight against Israel.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] During the war, the Lebanese Armed Forces did not engage in direct hostilities, but threatened retaliation if IDF troops pushed too far northward into Lebanon.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] In several instances, Lebanese troops fired anti-aircraft weapons at Israeli aircraft and attempted to disrupt landing operations.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] During the first days of the war, Lebanese Defense Minister Elias Murr said that "the Lebanese army will resist and defend the country.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] If there is an invasion of Lebanon, we are waiting for them." However, the Lebanese Army mostly stayed out of the fighting.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] According to a *Time* editorial, "to have stood up to the advancing Israeli armored columns would have been suicidal." On 7 August 2006, the seven-point plan was extended to include the deployment of 15,000 Lebanese Army troops to fill the void between an Israeli withdrawal and UNIFIL deployment.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] During the war, Hezbollah broadcaseted warnings in Hebrew and Arabic to specific Israeli communities regarding upcoming rocket attacks, and also sent text messages to warn Israeli residents to evacuate their homes to avoid being hit by rockets.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Similarly, the Israeli Air Force dropped 17,000 leaflets over Lebanon in 47 missions, and sent more than 700,000 computerized voice messages.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Many of them contained caricatures of Hassan Nasrallah and Hezbollah leading Lebanon to ruin and making civilians suffer, showing them as puppets of Iran and Syria, and calling on civilians to help remove Hezbollah.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] On 26 July, Israel dropped leaflets containing illustrations of nine tombstones with the name of a dead Hezbollah fighter on each one, in response to Nasrallah "deceiving" people on the number of Hezbollah casualties.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Another leaflet urged Hezbollah fighters to stop bleeding and fighting for Nasrallah, who sat safe in a bunker, to stop fighting against Lebanese national interests, and to return to their homes and families.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] On 11 August, Israel dropped leaflets accusing Hezbollah of hiding its "great losses", and containing the names of 90 to 100 Hezbollah fighters killed.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Israeli technicians also hacked into Al-Manar and broadcast clips, criticizing Nasrallah, showing the bodies of Hezbollah fighters, footage from Israeli raids and airstrikes, and captured Hezbollah equipment.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Terms for a ceasefire had been drawn and revised several times over the course of the conflict, yet successful agreement between the two sides took several weeks.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Hezbollah maintained the desire for an unconditional ceasefire, while Israel insisted upon a conditional ceasefire, including the return of the two seized soldiers.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Lebanon frequently pleaded for the United Nations Security Council to call for an immediate, unconditional ceasefire between Israel and Hezbollah.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] John Bolton confirmed that the US and UK, with support from several Arab leaders, delayed the ceasefire process.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Outsider efforts to interfere with a ceasefire only ended when it became apparent Hezbollah would not be easily defeated.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] On 11 August 2006 the United Nations Security Council unanimously approved UN Security Council Resolution 1701, in an effort to end the hostilities.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] It was accepted by the Lebanese government and Hezbollah on 12 August, and by the Israeli government on 13 August.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] The ceasefire took effect at 8:00 am (5:00 am GMT) on 14 August.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Before the ceasefire, the two Hezbollah members of cabinet said that their militia would not disarm south of the Litani River, according to another senior member of the Lebanese cabinet, while a top Hezbollah official similarly denied any intention of disarming in the south.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Israel said it would stop withdrawing from Southern Lebanon if Lebanese troops were not deployed there within a matter of days.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Under international humanitarian law, warring parties are obliged to distinguish between combatants and civilians, ensure that attacks on legitimate military targets are proportionate, and guarantee that the military advantage of such attacks outweigh the possible harm done to civilians.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Violations of these laws are considered war crimes.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Various groups and individuals accused both Israel and Hezbollah of violations of these laws during the conflict, and warned of possible war crimes.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] These allegations included intentional attacks on civilian populations or infrastructure, disproportionate or indiscriminate attacks, the use of human shields, and the use of prohibited weapons.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] No formal charges have been filed against either group.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Amnesty International called on both Hezbollah and Israel to end attacks on civilian areas during the conflict, and criticized attacks against civilian villages and infrastructure by Israel.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] They also highlighted IDF use of white phosphorus shells in Lebanon.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Human Rights Watch accused both parties of failing to distinguish between civilians and combatants, violating the principle of distinction, and committing war crimes.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] UN humanitarian chief Jan Egeland said Israel's response violated international humanitarian law, and criticized Hezbollah for "cowardly blending... among women and children." He also called Israel's use of over 100,000 cluster bombs "immoral".
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] According to Egeland, 90% of such bombs were launched by Israel in the last 3 days of combat, when it was known that a UN resolution was on its way.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Israel said that it tried to avoid civilians, and had distributed leaflets calling on civilian residents to evacuate, but that Hezbollah stored weapons in and fired from civilian areas, making those areas legitimate targets, and used civilians as human shields.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Amnesty International and Human Rights Watch found cases where Hezbollah did fire rockets from, and store weapons in, populated areas and deploy its forces among the civilian population; however, both say that is not conclusive evidence of the intent to use civilians as human shields.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Al-Jazeera reported at the time: "Foreign journalists based in Lebanon also reported that the Shia militia chose to fight from civilian areas and had on occasion prevented Lebanese civilians from fleeing conflict-hit areas of south Lebanon.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Images obtained by the *Sunday Herald Sun* show that "Hezbollah is waging war amid suburbia.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] The images ... show Hezbollah using high-density residential areas as launch pads for rockets and heavy-calibre weapons.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Amnesty International stated, however, that the volume of civilian casualties and damage to civilian infrastructure suggested that Israel was not just trying to target Hezbollah fighters.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] An AI spokesperson, Kate Gilmore, said that "[t]he pattern, scope and scale of the attacks makes Israel's claim that this was 'collateral damage', simply not credible".
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] "The evidence strongly suggests that the extensive destruction of power and water plants, as well as the transport infrastructure vital for food and other humanitarian relief, was deliberate and an integral part of a military strategy," Gilmore said.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] A 6 September 2007 Human Rights Watch report found that most of the civilian deaths in Lebanon resulted from "indiscriminate Israeli airstrikes", and found that Israeli aircraft targeted vehicles carrying fleeing civilians.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] In a statement issued before the report's release, the human rights organization said there was no basis to the Israeli government's claim that civilian casualties resulted from Hezbollah guerrillas using civilians as shields.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Kenneth Roth, Human Rights Watch executive director, said there were only "rare" cases of Hezbollah operating in civilian villages.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] "To the contrary, once the war started, most Hizbollah(sic) military officials and even many political officials left the villages," he said.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] On its final report, issued on 30 January 2008, the Israeli government's Winograd Commission concluded that the Israel Defense Forces did not commit violations or war crimes, as alleged by the Human Rights Watch, Amnesty International, and other NGOs.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] The Commission claimed that the evidence shows that the Israel Defense Forces did not target civilians, in contrast to Hezbollah and to denunciations by NGOs, and explained that terms like "war crimes" are without basis.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Both sides used cluster bombs during the conflict.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Israel fired 4.6 million submunitions into dozens of towns and villages in southern Lebanon in 962 separate strikes, around 90% within the final 72 hours of the war, when the conflict already had been largely resolved by UN Security Council Resolution 1701.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Entire towns were covered in cluster bombs.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] The unguided rockets were fired from mobile rocket launching platforms.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] To compensate for the inaccuracy of the rockets, the areas were flooded with munitions.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Israel claimed to have warned civilians prior to a strike, and that firing was limited to open areas or military targets inside urban areas.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Israel used advanced cluster munitions produced by Israel Military Industries, and large numbers of older cluster bombs, some produced in the 1970s, purchased from aging American stockpiles.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] These were fired by multiple rocket launchers, 155 mm artillery guns, and dropped by aircraft.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] As many as 1 million submunitions failed to explode on impact, lingering as land mines that killed or maimed almost 200 people since the war ended.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] As of 2011, munitions were still causing casualties and being cleared by volunteers.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Hezbollah fired 4,407 submunitions into civilian-populated areas of northern Israel in 113 separate strikes, using Chinese made Type-81 122 mm rockets, and Type-90 submunitions.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] These attacks killed one civilian and wounded twelve.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] Also phosphorus shells were used by the IDF to attack civilian areas in Lebanon.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] The shells were originally designed to generate a smoke screen in a battlefield situation, but white phosphorus is also especially harmful to humans because its burning will continue inside the flesh.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p01] The shelling was investigated as a violation of international law.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] The Lebanese civilian death toll is difficult to pinpoint as most published figures, including those released by the Lebanese government, do not distinguish between civilians and Hezbollah combatants.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] In addition, Hezbollah fighters can be difficult to identify as many do not wear military uniforms.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] However, it has been widely reported that the majority of the Lebanese killed were civilians, and UNICEF estimated that 30% of Lebanese killed were children under the age of 13.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] The Lebanese top police office and the Lebanon Ministry of Health, citing hospitals, death certificates, local authorities, and eyewitnesses, put the death toll at 1,123—37 soldiers and police officers, 894 identified victims, and 192 unidentified ones.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] The Lebanon Higher Relief Council (HRC) put the Lebanese death toll at 1,191, citing the health ministry and police, as well as other state agencies.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] The Associated Press estimated the figure at 1,035.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] In February 2007, the *Los Angeles Times* reported that at least 800 Lebanese had died during fighting, and other articles have estimated the figure to be at least 850.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Encarta states that *"estimates ... varied from about 850 to 1,200"* in its entry on Israel, while giving a figure of *"more than 1,200"* in its entry on Lebanon.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] The Lebanon Higher Relief Council estimated the number of Lebanese injured to be 4,409, 15% of whom were permanently disabled.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] The death toll estimates do not include Lebanese killed since the end of fighting by land mines or unexploded Israeli cluster bombs.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Between the end of the war and November 2008, approximately 40 people were killed and over 270 injured by cluster bombs.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] During the war Hezbollah kept a firm lid on its casualties.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Although it did sometimes announce casualty numbers in specific clashes, the party did not publish a comprehensive estimate for the duration of the war.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] A tally made by Associated Press counted to 70 dead Hezbollah fighters officially acknowledged by the party during the war.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Intelligence analysts Alastair Crooke and Mark Perry reported a few months after the war a total of 184 "Shiite martyr funerals" having been held in Lebanon since the war.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] They considered this number an indication of Hezbollah fatalities but warned that it could be revised upward in the future.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Four months after the end of the war the deputy chairman of the Hezbollah Political Council Mahmoud Qomati for the first time presented Hezbollah's official estimate of its losses.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] He claimed that 250 fighters had been killed in the war.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] The NGO Human Rights Watch (HRW) specifically studied 94 IDF air, artillery, and ground attacks during the war that claimed the lives of 561 persons.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Only 51 of these victims were Hezbollah combatants and about half of them were women or children.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] HRW said it documented the identities of another 548 fatalities, bringing the total of identified Lebanese deaths in the war to 1109.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] It argued (as an extrapolation from those 94 attacks) that an estimated 250 of these were Hezbollah combatants and the remaining 860 were civilians.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Lebanese officials cited in *The Daily Telegraph* estimated Hezbollah's losses at 500 killed.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] A UN official also estimated Hezbollah's losses at 500, though with not all of them being front-line fighters.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] The Israeli Military Intelligence (AMAN) in November 2006 estimated that some 650 Hezbollah operatives were killed, while over 800 were wounded.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Three years after the outbreak of war the Israel Foreign Affairs Ministry published a summary of the war which concluded that "over 600" Hezbollah fighters were killed in the war.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] (res.) Yaakov Amidror claimed that IDF had identified the names and addresses of 440 members of Hezbollah who were killed in the war.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Based on this number he estimated that the total amounted killed in the war to between 500 and 700.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] The Amal movement, a Shiite militia that fought alongside Hezbollah, suffered 17 dead.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Armed elements of the Lebanese Communist Party suffered twelve dead.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] The Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine – General Command, a Palestinian militia, lost two fighters in an Israeli air raid.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Cordesman (2007) wrote that some IDF officers claimed that "significant parts of the key [Hezbollah] leaders and cadres were killed or captured but Israel has given no details of such successes since the war".
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] On 19 July, a suspected bunker in southern Beirut was attacked with 23 tons of bombs.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Israeli intelligence leaked that 12 senior Hezbollah members had attended a meeting in the bunker and that among those killed was military chief Imad Mughniya.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Chairman Hassan Nasrallah himself was said to have been wounded in the attack.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] The IDF also claimed to have killed Abu Jaafar, the regional commander of central sector, in a clash in or air strike on Maroun ar-Ras.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Sheikh Nabil Qaouk, commander in South Lebanon was reportedly killed in a missile strike on a building in Tyre, where 13 civilians were wounded.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] All of these supposedly dead Hezbollah leaders later appeared in public seemingly unscathed.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] By the end of July, IDF claimed that about 40, mostly anonymous, "top-level commanders and officials" had been killed.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] IDF also named a few Hezbollah commanders who could not identified after the war, such as Jihad Attiya, said to be a logistical coordinator and Nour Shalhoub, a supposed arms transporter.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] In the beginning of August IDF reported that several "senior Hezbollah operatives" were killed in a commando raid on a building in Tyre.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Four years later IDF admitted that the senior Hezbollah figure, who was the target of the raid, was not killed but had escaped.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] During the war, Hezbollah never commented on these issues or simply offered flat denials.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] But shortly after the war (27 August), Hezbollah General-Secretary Hassan Nasrallah gave an interview to New TV, In this interview he conceded that between ten and twelve Hezbollah commanders had been killed in the war.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] None of the first or second levels of the leadership were harmed.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] But three commanders of the third level were killed; an operations officer in the Bint Jbeil axis, a logistics officer and a third commander involved in the military side of the party.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] In addition three or four town commanders and four or five village commanders were killed in the war.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Nasrallah did not mention any names but the killed commanders were later identified by Hezbollah newspaper *Al-Intiqad* (and later republished by Hezbollah magazine *al-Ahed*).
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] "Sajid ad-Duwayr" was the only dead Hezbullah commander correctly identified by IDF during the war.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] However, IDF did not learn his true identity (Muhammad Qanso) and got both the time and the place of his death wrong.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] He has not killed in the morning of 14 August and was not killed in either Bint Jbeil or Beirut's southern suburbs.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] And he was "a" commander, not "the" commander of Hezbollah Special Force.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Muhammad Abu Ta'am was commander of Hezbollah forces in the town Bint Jbeil.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] He was killed in the same air strike as sector commander Khalid Bazzi.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Two Hezbollah commanders were killed in battles around Wadi Hujeir/Wadi Sulouqi.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Rani Adnan Bazzi died in hand-to-hand combat, together with seven of his men, in the town of al-Ghandouriya, controlling the strategic wadi crossing.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] A further three fighters were wounded in the battle and one of them were taken prisoner by the IDF.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Commander Ali Mahmoud Salih ("Bilal") fought singlehandedly further up the wadi, firing ATGM rockets at the advancing Israeli tanks.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] In the end he was severely wounded by a drone strike and died some time later from his wounds.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] On 21 July, Israel Chief-of-Staff Dan Halutz presented one of the objective of the war as the "taking terrorists alive." He repeatedly ordered Israeli troops during the war to capture Hezbollah bodies "to show to the media".
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] On 24 July the IDF announced that it had captured two Hezbollah fighters in Battle of Maroun al-Ras, the first it had captured in the war.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Alon Friedman the prisoners were held in Israel.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] During a raid on Baakbek on 1 August, the IDF captured five Lebanese citizens, described by the IDF as "known Hezbollah gunmen".
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] All five were later identified as civilians and released three weeks later.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Israel claimed to have captured five Hezbollah fighters August 3, during a clash in Rajamin in which three Israeli soldiers were killed.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] On 8 August, Israel announced that it had also captured five Hezbollah "terrorists" in the Bint Jbeil area.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] The fighters were caught while sleeping and were carrying heavy weapons.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] A few days after the ceasefire IDF launched a second, seemingly unsuccessful, raid on Baalbek that led to the death of Lieutenant Colonel Emmanuel Moreno.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] According to *The Jerusalem Post*, two Hezbollah fighters were reportedly taken prisoner in the raid.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Most of the alleged Hezbollah fighters apprehended by IDF during the war, later turned out to be ordinary Lebanese civilians.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] At the end of the war, Israel held only four Hezbollah fighters as prisoners (plus a civilian Hezbollah member and former fighter).
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] None of them were commanders or Iranians.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] They were released in a prisoner swap with Israel in 2008.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Israel had also seized the bodies of twelve dead Hezbollah fighters and brought them to Israel.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] They were returned to Lebanon in the prisoner exchange.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Though rarely engaged in combat, 43 Lebanese soldiers and policemen were killed.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Hezbollah rockets and mortars killed 44 Israeli civilians during the conflict, including a severely wounded Haifa resident who died from his wounds more than a year after the war.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] In addition four elderly died of heart attacks during rocket attacks.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] At least 19 of the 46 Israeli civilians killed by Hezbollah rockets and mortars were Israeli Arabs (mainly Sunni Muslims).
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] The last civilian victim was an Israeli-Arab man who died on 30 August 2007, from injuries sustained in a rocket attack on Haifa.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] In addition, 4,262 civilians were injured—33 seriously wounded, 68 moderately, 1,388 lightly, and 2,773 suffered from shock and anxiety.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] A total of 121 IDF soldiers were killed in the war, including the two soldiers who were seized in the cross-border raid that started the war.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Their fates were not confirmed until their bodies were exchanged for Lebanese prisoners in 2008.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Of the IDF fatalities, 68 were privates or Non-Commission Officers, 27 Warrant Officers and 26 Officers (9 Lieutenants, 8 Captains, 8 Majors and one Colonel).
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Matériel losses in the Israeli Defense Forces accounted for fewer than 20 tanks, depending in the source.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Five tanks were damaged beyond repair ('lasting vehicle kills'), 22 tanks received armor penetrations, and 52 tanks suffered some form of damage.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Other sources claim 20 main battle tanks were destroyed (6 to mines, 14 to anti-tank guided missiles—all Merkava II, III or IV).
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Three helicopters were lost to accidents and one to Hezbollah missile fire.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] One fixed-wing F-16 was lost during take-off.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Three Hermes 450 drones were lost during the war, two by technical difficulties and one by an operator error.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] On 14 July, a Hezbollah operated a Chinese C-802 anti-ship missile, that struck the Israeli Navy's flagship INS *Hanit* killing 4 sailors and damaging the warship on the waterline, under the aft superstructure.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] The attack set the flight deck on fire and crippled the propulsion systems inside the hull.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] However, INS *Hanit* stayed afloat, withdrew and made the rest of the journey back to Ashdod port for repairs under its own power.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] The four crew members killed during the attack were: Staff Sergeant Tal Amgar, Corporal Shai Atas, Sergeant Yaniv Hershkovitz, and First Sergeant Dov Steinshuss.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Four United Nations Military Observers were killed and several more wounded.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] On 13 July 2006, and again on 15 July, the Israeli Air Force bombed the Jiyeh power station, 30 km (19 mi) south of Beirut, resulting in the largest-ever oil spill in the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] The plant's damaged storage tanks leaked an estimated 12,000 to 15,000 tonnes (more than 4 million gallons) of oil into the eastern Mediterranean.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] A 10-kilometre-wide (6.2 mi) oil slick covered 170 km (105 statute miles) of coastline, and threatened Turkey and Cyprus.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] The slick killed fish including the Atlantic bluefin tuna, a species already nearing extinction in the Mediterranean, and threatened the habitat of the endangered green sea turtle.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] It also potentially increased the risk of cancer in humans.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] An additional 25,000 tons of oil burned at the power station, creating a "toxic cloud" that rained oil downwind.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] The Lebanese government estimated it would take 10 years to recover from the damage of the strike.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] The UN estimated the cost for the initial clean-up at $64 million.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Hezbollah rocket attacks caused numerous forest fires inside northern Israel, particularly on the Naftali mountain range near Kiryat Shmona.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] As many as 16,500 acres (67 km2) of land, including forests and grazing fields, were destroyed by Hezbollah rockets.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] The Jewish National Fund estimated that it would take 50 to 60 years to rehabilitate the forests.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Israeli bombing also caused significant damage to the World Heritage Sites of Tyre and Byblos.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] In Tyre a Roman tomb was damaged and a fresco near the centre of the site collapsed.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] In Byblos, a medieval tower was damaged and Venetian-period remains near the harbour were dramatically stained by the oil slick and were considered to be difficult to clean.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Damage was also caused to remains at Bint Jbeil and Chamaa, and to the Temple of Bacchus in Baalbek.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Damage to various industries occurred during the war.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] A report from the Lebanese Council for Development and Reconstruction (CDR) said that the IDF bombing campaign had destroyed more than 900 small and medium enterprises with damage to Lebanon's civilian infrastructure estimated close to US$2.5 billion.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] The material damage to the private sector was estimated at $200 million with an anticipated increase in that figure due to cancelled contracts.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Other repair and rebuilding costs resulting from the bombing include power supplies ($208m), telecoms ($99m), water ($74m) and military installations ($16m).
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] The Lebanese national airline, MEA, had also been grounded for the duration of the conflict.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Agricultural activity, particularly in south Lebanon, was abandoned due to the fighting and bombing of the irrigation system.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Tourism, which accounts for 15% of Lebanon's GDP, has been severely disrupted by the conflict.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Damage to communal and business infrastructure, the Israeli-imposed sea-and-air blockade and continued instability is preventing and deterring tourists.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Foreign visitors had been expected to bring in $2.5 to $3 billion US during 2006.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] IDF bombing has damaged irrigation canals, open water channels, and underground water diversion pipes which run Litani River water to more than 10,000 acres (40 km2) of farmland, villages in southern Lebanon and the Bekaa Valley.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] These attacks have been criticised as an attempt to "lay claim to Lebanon's prime watersheds".
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Attacks on the Litani Dam were also criticised.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Israeli officials explained the damage to the water infrastructures was unintentional and collateral to attacks on roads and bridges used by Hezbollah.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] The international journalists' representative body, Reporters without Borders, reported that, to its knowledge, the IDF had damaged transmitting equipment in the Satka area of Beirut and reduced the premises of Al Manar to ruins.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] The IDF contend that the Al-Manar TV facilities which they bombed represent the propaganda arm of Hezbollah and were a legitimate target for the IDF military.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Reporters Without Borders disputes this saying that the station "cannot be viewed as [a] military" target.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] The governments of the United States, United Kingdom, Germany, Australia, and Canada asserted Israel's right to self-defense.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] The United States government further responded by authorizing Israel's request for expedited shipment of precision-guided bombs, but did not announce the decision publicly.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Bush said he thought the conflict was part of the "war on terrorism".
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] On 20 July 2006, the United States Congress voted overwhelmingly to support Israel's "right to defend itself".
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Among neighboring Middle Eastern nations, Iran, Syria, and Yemen voiced strong support for Hezbollah.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] A*Ynet* report claimed Iranian soldiers were fighting in the war itself, with some sources asserting Iranian commander Qasem Soleimani advised Hezbollah for its defense from Israel.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] The Islamic Courts Union of Somalia was also reported to have fought alongside Hezbollah.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] On the other hand, the Arab League, Egypt, and Jordan issued statements criticizing Hezbollah's actions and declaring support for Lebanon.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Saudi Arabia found Hezbollah entirely responsible.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Many worldwide protests and demonstrations appealed for an immediate ceasefire on both sides and expressed concern for the heavy loss of civilian life on all sides.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Other demonstrations were held exclusively in favor of Lebanon or Israel.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Numerous newspaper advertising campaigns, SMS and email appeals, and online petitions also occurred.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Various foreign governments assisted the evacuation of their citizens from Lebanon.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] The 2007 report "'War to the Last Moment': The Israeli Media in the Second Lebanon War" by the Israeli media monitoring NGO Keshev (trans.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] "Awareness") stated that the Israeli media "except for a few exceptional instances ... covered the war in an almost entirely mobilized manner" serving more to support the goals of the Israeli government and IDF than to objectively report the news.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] "The media created a general atmosphere of complete and absolute support and justification of the war, and systematically suppressed questions that arose as early as the first day of fighting. ...
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] The criticism gradually increased toward the end of the war-as it became clearer that the IDF was not managing to win.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] According to the report, "significant coverage of the decision-making process was almost entirely absent in Israel's media" at the beginning of the war and reports on the status of Israelis living in the North who did not receive proper governmental support were marginalized.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Further, the report states that the media unreasonably centered on the question of the loyalties of Arab-Israelis in the North instead of focusing on inadequate provision of services by the state.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] The report acknowledges that the Israeli media reported on Lebanese suffering, But states that it divorced the suffering from the IDF operations causing it.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Finally, with regard to diplomacy, Israeli media buried the stories on negotiations to reflect the derision held by decision-makers toward a diplomatic solution.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] On 18 July 2006 Hezbollah Press Officer Hussein Nabulsi took CNN's Nic Robertson on an exclusive tour of southern Beirut.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Robertson noted that despite his minder's anxiety about explosions in the area, it was clear that Hezbollah had sophisticated media relations and were in control of the situation.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Several media commentators and journalists have alleged an intentionally distorted coverage of the events, in favour of Hezbollah, by means of photo manipulation, staging by Hezbollah or by journalists, and false or misleading captioning.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] As another example, Reuters withdrew over 900 photographs by Adnan Hajj, a Lebanese freelance photographer, after he admitted to digitally adding and darkening smoke spirals in photographs of an attack on Beirut.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Photographs submitted to Reuters and Associated Press showed one Lebanese woman mourning on two different pictures taken by two photographers, allegedly taken two weeks apart.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] It is "common practice to send more than one photographer to an incident".
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Social and online media were important for providing alternate means of creating and disseminating accounts and political commentary.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] For example, Lebanese blogger Fink Ployd maintained the blog BloggingBeirut.com, posting images, audio files, and testimony from Lebanon, particularly from Lebanese Arab youth.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Also he was ordered not to report Hizbollah rocket attacks on Israeli civilians.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Following the UN-brokered ceasefire, there were mixed responses on who had gained or lost the most in the war.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Iran and Syria proclaimed a victory for Hezbollah while Olmert declared that the war was a success for Israel.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] At the outbreak of hostilities, Prime Minister Fouad Siniora promised to rein in Hezbollah in an effort to stop Israel's offensive.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Saniora said that there could be no sovereign state of Lebanon without the group's disarming.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] The former President of Lebanon Amin Gemayel, a longtime critic of Hezbollah said, "Hezbollah took a unilateral action, but its repercussions will affect the entire country." The war deepened the longtime divide in Lebanon over Hezbollah's role.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Many admired the organization for being the sole group to fight against Israel.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Others considered it to be a dangerous militia that executes Iran and Syria policies in Lebanon.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] The divide over Hezbollah followed mostly sectarian lines, with Shias largely supporting the group and Sunnis, Christians and Druze mostly opposing it.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] On 27 August 2006, Nasrallah said in an interview with New TV that the abduction of the two soldiers did not cause the war.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] It only advanced a long planned war for a few months.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] But he added: "If there was even a 1 percent chance that the July 11 capturing operation would have led to a war like the one that happened, would you have done it?
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] I would say no, absolutely not, for humanitarian, moral, social, security, military, and political reasons. [...] What happened is not an issue of a reaction to a capturing operation... what happened was already planned for.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Within hours of Israeli's bombing of Lebanon on 13 July 2006, hundreds of protesters gathered in Tel Aviv to oppose the war.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] On 22 July, about 2,000 people, including many Arab citizens of Israel, demanded an end to the offensive during a protest march in Tel Aviv's Rabin Square.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] On 5 August, some Israelis demonstrated in Tel Aviv, including former Knesset members of the Meretz party, Mossi Raz, Naomi Hazan and Yael Dayan.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Initially, in a poll by an Israeli radio station, Israelis were split on the outcome with the majority believing that no one won.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] By 25 August 63% of Israelis polled wanted Olmert to resign due to his handling of the war.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] The Israeli Chief of Staff Dan Halutz admitted to failings in the conflict.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] On 15 August, Israeli government and defense officials called for Halutz's resignation following a stock scandal in which he admitted selling stocks hours before the start of the Israeli offensive.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Halutz subsequently resigned on 17 January 2007.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] On 21 August, a group of demobilized Israel reserve soldiers and parents of soldiers killed in the fighting started a movement calling for the resignation of Olmert and the establishment of a state commission of inquiry.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] They set up a protest tent opposite the Knesset and grew to over 2,000 supporters by 25 August, including the influential Movement for Quality Government.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] These would have a more limited mandate and less authority than a single inquiry commission headed by a retired judge.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] The political and military committees were to be headed by former director of Mossad Nahum Admoni and former chief of staff Amnon Lipkin-Shahak, respectively.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Critics argued that these committees amount to a whitewash, due to their limited authority, limited investigatory scope, their self-appointed basis, and that neither would be headed by a retired judge.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Due to these pressures, on 11 October, Admoni was replaced by retired justice Eliyahu Winograd as chair of the political probe, and the probe itself was elevated to the status of governmental commission with near-state commission mandate: the Winograd Commission.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] On 12 September, former defense minister Moshe Arens spoke of "the defeat of Israel" in calling for a state committee of inquiry.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] IDF Major General Yiftah Ron Tal, on 4 October 2006 became the second and highest ranking serving officer to express his opinion that the IDF failed "to win the day in the battle against Hezbollah" as well as calling for Lt.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Ron-Tal was subsequently fired for making those and other critical comments.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] In March 2007, the Committee decided to name the war the "Second Lebanon War", a decision that was subsequently approved by the Israeli cabinet.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Israeli military historian Martin van Creveld stated that Israel's war against Hezbollah was indeed "marked by a long series of failures" but he criticized the Winograd Commission for its failure to take into account the substantial achievements of the war.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] He noted that hundreds of Hezbollah fighters were killed in the war, and that the organization had "the fight knocked out of it", since following the war, Israel experienced a level of calm on its Lebanon border not seen since the mid-1960s.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] He also noted that Hezbollah was "thrown out of South Lebanon", and was replaced by "a fairly robust United Nations peacekeeping force" to prevent its return.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Thomas Friedman concurred, stating that the war was a "huge strategic loss for Hezbollah", and contrasted the billions in damage suffered by Hezbollah and Lebanon with the "relatively minor damage" suffered by Israel, which enjoyed an economic "growth spurt" immediately following the war.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Some Israeli sources stated that due to unprecedented Iranian military support to Hezbollah before and during the war, some consider it the first round of the Iran–Israel proxy conflict, rather than a continuation of the Arab–Israeli conflict.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] According to the Winograd Commission report, the Second Lebanon War was regarded as a "missed opportunity" and that "Israel initiated a long war, which ended without a defined military victory".
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Following a long period of using standoff firepower and limited ground activities, the IDF launched a large-scale ground offensive close to the UN Security Council's resolution which imposed a ceasefire.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] In the aftermath of the conflict US President George Bush said that Hezbollah was responsible for starting the war, and that the group suffered a defeat at the hands of Israel.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] He also said that Israel "mishandled its opportunity", and that some of the sites it attacked were of "questionable military value".
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Military analyst and former IDF general Giora Eiland concluded that, though outgunned and outnumbered, Hezbollah managed to hold off Israel's advanced armed forces and proved its ability to damage Israel by launching rockets at its territory until the end of the war.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] He estimates that Hezbollah's destructive capabilities have increased in the years after the war and that the group is capable to inflict "far worse damage on the Israeli homefront" than in 2006.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] An Israeli official warned that combat with Hezbollah will be very bloody and Lebanon would sustain heavy damage in any future war.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] British military historian John Keegan stated that the outcome of the war was "misreported as an Israeli defeat" due to anti-Israel bias in the international media.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] He concluded that Hezbollah had suffered heavy losses, and that a ceasefire came into effect before Israel could completely dislodge Hezbollah from its positions.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] He also stated that the casualties sustained by Israel during the war had alarmed the Israeli Government and High Command because Israel's small population is acutely vulnerable to losses in battle.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Hezbollah may have won the propaganda war, but on the ground it lost.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Michael Young, opinion-page editor at the Lebanese *Daily Star* newspaper, stated that Hezbollah turned "the stench of defeat into the smell of victory", through clever use of its propaganda machine.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] American military strategist and historian Edward Luttwak drew comparisons with the 1973 Yom Kippur War, where what initially looked like an Israeli setback later turned out to be an IDF victory and an Arab defeat.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] He stated that although some IDF tanks were penetrated by missiles, they also largely limited IDF casualties, and that Hezbollah had failed to inflict massive losses on the IDF and to kill large numbers of Israelis in rocket attacks.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Journalist Michael Totten wrote that "Hezbollah lost and Hezbollah knows it." He questioned why Hezbollah did not attack Israel when the IDF attacked Hamas in Gaza in 2008, and noted that most of Nasrallah's supporters "want Hezbollah to deter Israeli invasions, not to invite Israeli invasions".
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Armin Rosen, Defense and military advisor wrote at Business Insider that the 2006 Lebanon War was "widely remembered as one of the worst debacles in the history of the Israeli military", but remarked that it established Israeli deterrence against Hezbollah.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] The fighting resulted in a huge financial setback for Lebanon, with an official estimate of a fall in growth from +6% to 2% and US$5 billion (22% of GDP) in direct and indirect costs, while the cost for Israel was estimated at US$3.5 billion.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] Indirect costs to Israel include a cut in growth by 0.9%. and the cost to tourism was estimated at 0.4% of Israel's GDP in the following year.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p02] According to Imad Salamey in *The Government and Politics of Lebanon*, the main casualty was the fragile unity between Lebanon's sectarian and political groups.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] In the days following 14 August 2006 ceasefire, Hezbollah launched dozens of rockets and mortars inside southern Lebanon, which Israel did not respond to, though there were several instances where Israeli troops killed armed Hezbollah members approaching their positions.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] Israeli warplanes continued conducting numerous flyovers and maneuvers above southern Lebanon, which Israel said did not violate the ceasefire.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] On 19 August 2006, Israel launched a raid in Lebanon's eastern Beqaa Valley it says was aimed at disrupting Hezbollah's weapons supply from Syria and Iran.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] France, then leading UNIFIL, also issued criticism of the flyovers, which it interpreted as aggressive.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] Israel argued that "[t]he ceasefire is based on (UN resolution) 1701 which calls for an international arms embargo against Hezbollah," and said the embargo could be lifted after full implementation of the ceasefire but Annan said that UNIFIL would only interdict arms at Lebanon's request.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] On 7 September 2006 and 8 September 2006, respectively, aviation and naval blockades were lifted.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] In the second half of September Hezbollah claimed victory and asserted an improvement in their position, and they redeployed to some positions on the border as Israel completed its withdrawal from Lebanon save border-straddling Ghajar.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] On 3 October, an Israeli fighter penetrated the two-nautical-mile (4 km) defence perimeter of the French frigate *Courbet* without answering radio calls, triggering a diplomatic incident.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] On 24 October, six Israeli F-16s flew over a German Navy vessel patrolling off Israel's coast just south of the Lebanese border.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] The German Defence Ministry said that the planes had given off infrared decoys and one of the aircraft had fired two shots into the air, which had not been specifically aimed.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] The Israeli military said that a German helicopter took off from the vessel without having coordinated this with Israel, and denied vehemently having fired any shots at the vessel and said "as of now" it also had no knowledge of the jets launching flares over it.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] Israeli Defence Minister Amir Peretz telephoned his German counterpart Franz Josef Jung to clarify that 'Israel has no intention to carry out any aggressive actions' against the German peacekeeping forces in Lebanon, who are there as part of UNIFIL to enforce an arms embargo against Hezbollah.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] Germany confirmed the consultations, and that both sides were interested in maintaining good cooperation.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] On 1 December 2006, UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan submitted a report to the Security Council president maintaining "there were no serious incidents or confrontations" since the ceasefire in August 2006.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] In one case, a UNIFIL demining team was challenged by two Hezbollah members in combat uniforms armed with AK-47 rifles; UNIFIL notified the Lebanese army, who arrested three suspects the next day.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] Annan also reported that as of 20 November 2006, 822 Israeli cluster bomb strike sites had been recorded, with 60,000 cluster bomblets having been cleared by the UN Mine Action Coordination Center.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] The Winograd report severely criticized Olmert, accusing him of a "severe failure in exercising judgment, responsibility and caution." Lebanese Prime Minister Fouad Siniora criticized the Winograd report for failing to report on the full destruction dealt to Lebanon by the brief July War of 2006.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] After the war, the Lebanese Army deployed 15,000 soldiers, backed by a UNIFIL force of 12,000, deployed South of the Litani River to replace Hezbollah, although the Lebanese government said that it cannot and will not disarm Hezbollah by force.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] On 7 February 2010, the Lebanese Army fired at an Israeli bulldozer on the border, and Israeli forces returned fire.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] Lebanon claimed that the bulldozer had crossed the border and entered Lebanese territory.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] On 21 February 2007, Lebanese Army troops fired at an Israeli UAV over Tyre with small arms, causing no damage.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] On 12 February 2008, Imad Mugniyah, the head of Hezbollah's military wing, was assassinated by a car bomb in Damascus.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] The Mossad, Israel's intelligence agency, was widely believed to be behind the assassination.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] Although Israel officially denied involvement, Mugniyah had been the target of previous Mossad assassination attempts.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] Israel considered Mugniyah a "significant force behind actions against Israel".
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] On 14 July 2009, an explosion in Khirbat Silim, a Lebanese village near the Lebanon-Israel border, killed eight Hezbollah militants.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] Israel and the United Nations stated that the explosion was a hidden Hezbollah weapons cache, and condemned Hezbollah for violating Resolution 1701.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] The Lebanese government stated that the explosion was caused by IDF munitions left following the 2006 war.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] Hezbollah blamed the explosion on leftover shells that had been collected following Israel's withdrawal from Lebanon in 2000.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] A Kuwaiti newspaper, *al-Seyassah*, reported that the ammunition warehouse stored chemical weapons.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] On 23 August 2009, the IDF published a video it said showed villagers from Marwakhin, a village in southern Lebanon, "forcefully resisting" efforts by Hezbollah militants to store weapons in their village.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] On 4 November 2009 Israeli navy commandos of Shayetet 13 boarded the ship MV *Francop* in the eastern Mediterranean Sea and seized 500 tons of Iranian armaments disguised as civilian cargo.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] Israel said the weapons were bound for Hezbollah and originated from Iran.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] According to Lebanese Army in May 2010 it fired anti-aircraft artillery at two Israeli jets over Lebanon.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] In 2010, French UNIFIL forces warned that they could in the future attack Israeli jets with anti-aircraft batteries if Israel continued its overflights of Lebanese airspace.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] On 4 August 2010, a clash on the border occurred when the Israel military tried to remove a tree from between the border and the border fence on Israeli territory.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] According to the Israelis, the tree was blocking the view of one of their video cameras at the border.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] The Lebanese army fired at the Israeli forces and there was a clash for a few hours.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] In the ensuing clash, one Israeli soldier died as well as two Lebanese soldiers and one Lebanese journalist.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] There were also a number of injured military soldiers and civilians on both sides including Lebanese journalists.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] Until that time, Hezbollah had provided no information on Goldwasser and Regev's condition and disallowed the Red Cross from visiting them.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] The 2006 Lebanon War is the subject of two feature length films, both of which were screened at the 2008 Sundance Film Festival.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] They are Philippe Aractingi's *Under the Bombs* (2007) and Guy Nattiv and Erez Tadmor's *Strangers* (2007).
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] Israeli soldier and documentary filmmaker Yariv Mozer also wrote, directed and filmed the autobiographical "My First War" based on his experiences in the conflict.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] The conflict was also the subject of an episode of *Anthony Bourdain: No Reservations*, which was nominated for an Emmy Award for Outstanding Informational Programming in 2007.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] A collective of Lebanese filmmakers produced during and in the immediate aftermath of the war some twenty short videos that were released as *Videos Under Siege* and presented in numerous festivals including the Dubai International Film Festival.
[src:maritime-history/2006-lebanon-war-p03] The directors involved included Akram Zaatari, Khalil Joreige, Joana Hadjithomas, Danielle Arbid, Tina Baz, Gregory Buchakjian, Ghassan Salhab, Rania Stephan and others.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The **Abbasid Caliphate** or **Abbasid Empire** was the third Islamic caliphate, ruled by the Abbasid dynasty.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The dynasty was descended from Muhammad's uncle, Abbas ibn Abd al-Muttalib (d.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The Abbasids rose to power in 750, when the Abbasid Revolution overthrew the preceding Umayyad Caliphate, and they ruled as caliphs from their metropole in Iraq until 1258, with Baghdad as their capital for most of their history.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The Abbasid Revolution had its origins and first successes in the easterly region of Khurasan, far from the Levantine center of Umayyad influence.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The Abbasids first centered their government in Kufa, Iraq, but in 762 the second caliph al-Mansur founded the city of Baghdad and made it the capital.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Baghdad became a center of science, culture, arts, and invention, ushering in what became known as the Golden Age of Islam.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] It hosted several key academic institutions, such as the House of Wisdom, as well as a multi-ethnic and multi-religious population, which made the city famous as a centre of learning across the world.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The Abbasid period was marked by the use of bureaucrats in government, including the vizier, as well as a growing inclusion of non-Arab Muslims in the *ummah* (Muslim community) and among the political elites.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The height of Abbasid power and prestige is traditionally associated with the reign of Harun al-Rashid (r.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] After his death, a civil war brought new divisions and was followed by significant changes to the character of the state, including the creation of a new professional army recruited mainly from Turkic slaves and the construction of a new capital, Samarra, in 836.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The 9th century also saw many provinces becoming increasingly autonomous, giving rise to local dynasties that controlled different regions of the empire, such as the Aghlabids, Tahirids, Samanids, Saffarids, and Tulunids.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] After a period of turmoil in the 860s, the caliphate regained some stability and its seat returned to Baghdad in 892.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] During the 10th century, the caliphs were reduced to mere figureheads, with real political and military power resting in the hands of the Iranian Buyids and the Seljuq Turks, who took control of Baghdad in 945 and 1055, respectively.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The Abbasids eventually regained control of Iraq during the reign of Caliph al-Muqtafi (r.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] 1136–1160) and extended their rule into Iran during the reign of Caliph al-Nasir (r.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] This revival ended in 1258 with the sack of Baghdad by the Mongols under Hulagu Khan and the execution of Caliph al-Musta'sim, which marked the effective end of the Abbasid Caliphate.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] A surviving branch of the Abbasid dynasty was formally reinstated in 1261 by the Mamluk sultans in Cairo, but it lacked any political power.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The dynasty continued to claim symbolic authority until the Ottoman conquest of Egypt in 1517, the last Abbasid caliph being al-Mutawakkil III.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The Abbasid caliphs descended from Abbas ibn Abd al-Muttalib, one of the youngest uncles of Muhammad and of the same Banu Hashim clan.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] This family relation to Muhammad made them appealing to those who were discontented with the rule of the Umayyad caliphs (661–750), who did not descend from the same family.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Over the course of their rule, the Umayyads even suppressed several rebellions that attempted to bring other members of Muhammad's family to power.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] One of the claims that the Abbasids made in the early years of their political movement was that Abu Hashim, the son of Muhammad ibn al-Hanafiyya and grandson of Ali, had formally transferred the Imamate (*imāmah*) to Muhammad ibn Ali (the great-grandson of Abbas) and thus to the Abbasid family.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Muhammad ibn Ali began to campaign in Persia for the return of power to the family of Muhammad, the Hashemites, in the context of the reign of Umar II.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Later, after they had attained power and needed to broaden their support among Muslims, the Abbasids supplemented this claim with other claims to justify their legitimacy.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The Abbasids also distinguished themselves from the Umayyads by attacking their moral character and administration in general.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The Abbasids also appealed to non-Arab Muslims, known as *mawali*, who remained outside the kinship-based society of the Arabs and were perceived as a lower class within the Umayyad empire.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] According to Ira Lapidus, "The Abbasid revolt was supported largely by Arabs, mainly the aggrieved settlers of Merv with the addition of the Yemeni faction and their Mawali".
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] During the reign of Marwan II, this opposition culminated in the rebellion of Ibrahim al-Imam, the fourth in descent from Abbas.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Supported by the province of Khurasan (eastern Iran), even though the governor opposed them, and the Shi'i Arabs, he achieved considerable success, but was captured and died in prison in 749.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] On 9 June 747 (15 Ramadan AH 129), Abu Muslim, rising from Khurasan, successfully initiated an open revolt against Umayyad rule, which was carried out under the sign of the Black Standard.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Close to 10,000 soldiers were under Abu Muslim's command when the hostilities officially began in Merv.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] General Qahtaba followed the fleeing governor Nasr ibn Sayyar west defeating the Umayyads at the Battle of Gorgan, the Battle of Nahavand and finally in the Battle of Karbala, all in the year 748.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Ibrahim was captured by Marwan and was killed.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The quarrel was taken up by Ibrahim's brother Abdallah, known by the name of Abu al-'Abbas al-Saffah, who defeated the Umayyads in 750 in the battle near the Great Zab river and was subsequently proclaimed caliph.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] After this loss, Marwan fled to Egypt, where he was subsequently killed.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The remainder of his family, barring one male, were also eliminated.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] 750–754) was spent consolidating Abbasid rule over the Muslim community.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Soon after the victory of 750, Abu Muslim sent forces to Central Asia to confront an army from Tang China led by Gao Xianzhi.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Gao Xianzhi and his army were defeated in 751 at the Battle of Talas, near present-day Tashkent, by the Abbasid army under Ziyad ibn Salih.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] This defeat marked the end of Tang influence in Transoxiana and halted Tang westward expansion.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The Abbasids then consolidated their rule in Transoxania.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Elsewhere, the Abbasids focused on putting down numerous rebellions in Syria and Iraq.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The Byzantines conducted raids during these early distractions.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] One of the first major changes effected by Abbasid rule was the move of the caliphate's center of power from Syria to Iraq.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] This was closer to the Persian *mawali* support base of the Abbasids and the move addressed their demand for reduced Arab dominance in the empire.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] However, no definitive capital was yet selected.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] In these early Abbasid years, Kufa generally served as the administrative capital, but the caliphs were wary of the Alid sympathies in the city and did not always reside here.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] In 752, al-Saffah built a new city called al-Hashimiyya, at an uncertain location, most likely near Kufa.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Later that same year, he moved to Anbar, where he built a new settlement for his Khurasani soldiers and a palace for himself.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] It was al-Saffah's successor, Abu Ja'far al-Mansur (r.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] 754–775) who firmly consolidated Abbasid rule and faced down internal challenges.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] His uncle, Abdallah ibn Ali, the victor over the Umayyads at the Battle of the Zab, was the most serious potential rival for leadership and al-Mansur sent Abu Muslim, the Khurasani revolutionary commander, against him in 754.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] After Abu Muslim successfully defeated him, al-Mansur then turned to eliminate Abu Muslim himself.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] He arranged to have him arrested and executed in 755.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] On the western frontier, the Abbasids were unable to re-assert caliphal control over the western and central Maghreb, which the Umayyads had lost in the 740s.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] One member of the Umayyad dynasty, Abd ar-Rahman, also managed to escape the purge of his family and established independent rule in al-Andalus (present-day Spain and Portugal) in 756, founding the Umayyad emirate of Córdoba.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] In 756, al-Mansur had also sent over 4,000 Arab mercenaries to assist the Tang dynasty against the rebel leader An Lushan.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The Abbasids, or "Black Flags" as they were commonly called, were known in Tang dynasty chronicles as the *hēiyī Dàshí*, "The Black-robed Tazi" (黑衣大食) ("Tazi" being a borrowing from Persian *Tāzī*, the word for "Arab").
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Later, Caliph Harun al-Rashid sent embassies to China and established good relations with the Tang emperors.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] After the war, these embassies remained in China and al-Rashid established an alliance with China.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Several embassies from the Abbasid caliphs to the Chinese court have been recorded in the *Old Book of Tang*, the most important being those of al-Saffah, al-Mansur, and Harun al-Rashid.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] In 762, al-Mansur suppressed a rebellion in the Hejaz led by al-Nafs al-Zakiyya, a descendant from Ali ibn Abi Talib, whose challenge to the Abbasid claim to leadership was based on his Alid lineage and thus presented a serious political threat.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] He was defeated by an Abbasid army led by Isa ibn Musa.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] It was after this victory, in 762, that al-Mansur finally established a proper Abbasid capital, Baghdad – officially called *Madinat al-Salam* ('City of Peace') – located on the Tigris River, near the former ancient capital city of Ctesiphon.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Prior to this, he had continued to consider multiple sites for a capital, including al-Hashimiyya, which he used as a capital for a while, and al-Rumiyya (near the ruins of Ctesiphon), which he used for a few months.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Various other sites in the region also appear to have served as "capitals" under either al-Saffah or al-Mansur prior to the founding of Baghdad.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Al-Mansur centralised the judicial administration and, later, Harun al-Rashid established the institution of Great Qadi to oversee it.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The Umayyad empire was mostly Arab; however, the Abbasids progressively became made up of more and more converted Muslims in which the Arabs were only one of many ethnicities.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The Abbasids had depended heavily on the support of Persians in their overthrow of the Umayyads.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Al-Mansur welcomed non-Arab Muslims to his court.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] While this helped integrate Arab and Persian cultures, it alienated many of their Arab supporters, particularly the Khurasani Arabs who had supported them in their battles against the Umayyads.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] It was also during this early period of the dynasty, in particular during the rule of al-Mansur, Harun al-Rashid, and al-Ma'mun, that its reputation and power were created.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The position of *wazir* (vizier) developed in this period.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] It was initially akin to a secretary, but under the tenure of the Barmakids, an Iranian family close to the Abbasids, the position became powerful and Harun al-Rashid delegated state affairs to them for many years.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] This resulted in a more ceremonial role for many Abbasid caliphs compared with caliphal rule under the Umayyads; the viziers began to exert greater influence, and the role of the caliph's aristocracy was slowly replaced by a Barmakid bureaucracy.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] At the western end of the empire, Harun al-Rashid agreed to grant the province of Ifriqiya (centered in present-day Tunisia) as a hereditary emirate to Ibrahim ibn al-Aghlab, who founded the Aghlabid dynasty there.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] 786–809), the Abbasid Empire reached its peak.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] 775–785), restarted the fighting with the Byzantines, and his sons continued the conflict until Empress Irene pushed for peace.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] After several years of peace, Nikephoros I broke the treaty, then fended off multiple incursions during the first decade of the 9th century.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] These Abbasid attacks pushed into the Taurus Mountains, culminating with a victory at the Battle of Krasos and the massive invasion of 806, led by al-Rashid himself.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Harun al-Rashid's navy also proved successful, taking Cyprus.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Al-Rashid then focused on the rebellion of Rafi ibn al-Layth in Khurasan and died while there.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Domestically, al-Rashid pursued policies similar to those of his father al-Mahdi.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] He released many of the Umayyads and Alids his brother al-Hadi (r.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] 785–786) had imprisoned and declared amnesty for all political groups of the Quraysh.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] While Baghdad remained the official capital, al-Rashid chose to reside in Raqqa from 796 until the end of his reign.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] In 802, he established an unusual succession plan which decreed that his son al-Amin would inherit the title of Caliph and have control of Iraq and the western empire while his other son al-Ma'mun would rule Khurasan and most eastern parts of the empire.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] In 803, he turned on and imprisoned or killed most of the Barmakids, who had wielded administrative power on his behalf.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The reasons for this sudden and ruthless move remain unclear and have been the subject of much discussion by contemporary writers and later historians.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Al-Rashid's decision to split the succession proved to be damaging to the longevity of the empire.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] After his death in 809, his succession pact eventually collapsed and the empire was split by a civil war between al-Amin in Iraq and al-Ma'mun in Khurasan.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] This ended with a successful siege of Baghdad by al-Ma'mun's forces.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] When the city fell in 813, al-Amin was captured and executed on the orders of al-Ma'mun's general, Tahir ibn Husayn.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] This marked the first time that an Abbasid ruler was publicly executed and it irrevocably damaged the prestige of the caliphate.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Al-Ma'mun became caliph and ruled until his death in 833.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] He initially ruled the empire from his established base in Merv, Khurasan, where his main support was found, but this prolonged the discontent and instability in Iraq and triggered further fighting in the years following his victory.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] In 817, he officially declared an Alid, 'Ali al-Rida, as his heir, instead of an Abbasid family member, perhaps hoping to promote Muslim unity, but the move backfired.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Eventually, he was compelled to step back from these policies and move his court to Baghdad, where he arrived in August 819.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] After this, the rest of his reign was relatively peaceful.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Exceptions included a rebellion in Azerbaijan by the Khurramites, supported by the Byzantines, which continued until 837.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] He also repulsed a Byzantine attack on Syria around 829, followed by counter-attacks into Anatolia, and suppressed a rebellion in Egypt in 832.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The later years of al-Ma'mun's reign are known for his intellectual interests and patronage.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The so-called "translation movement" — the state-sponsored translation of scientific and literary works of antiquity into Arabic — that had begun under his predecessors was pushed even further during this time and al-Ma'mun shifted its focus to ancient Greek works of science and philosophy.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] In matters of religion, his interest in philosophy spurred him to endorse Mu'tazilism, the rationalist school of Islamic thought.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Under its influence, he officially endorsed the doctrine of createdness of the Qur'an in 827.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] In 833, he went further and forcibly imposed it on the *ulama*, the Sunni religious scholars.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] This controversial policy, known as the *Mihna*, was eventually abandoned in 848.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Ultimately, it failed to convince the Sunni *ulama* and instead contributed to the emergence of the latter as a more cohesive social class whose views and interests did not always align with the caliph.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Following the civil war between al-Amin and al-Ma'mun, the traditional mainstay of the Abbasid army, the *Khurasaniyya* and *'Abna al-dawla*, were no longer seen as reliable and the caliphs sought to recruit a new type of army whose loyalty could be better assured.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] This process began under al-Ma'mun but it is his brother and successor, al-Mu'tasim (r.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] 833–842), who is known for its more radical implementation.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Soldiers were recruited from several new sources, but the most important, especially under al-Mu'tasim, were the group referred to by Arabic chronicles as "Turks" (*atrāk*), who appear to have been mainly Turkic people from Central Asia.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Some modern scholars refer to them as Mamluks, marking them as the antecedent of the later slave-soldiers known by that term, but their exact legal status has been a subject of scholarly debate.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Many, perhaps the majority, were originally purchased or captured slaves, but they were paid regular salaries and thus likely manumitted.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] In any case, these outsiders did not have political ties among the traditional elites and thus their loyalty was to the caliph alone.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] These troops were likely the first standing army of the caliphate and provided the caliph with a strong base of military support.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] However, the influx of new foreign troops into the capital created tensions with its inhabitants and with older elites.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] This was one of the main reasons why, in 836, al-Mu'tasim decided to found a new capital, Samarra, on an open site to the north of Baghdad.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The new capital housed the caliph's army, allowed for the unhindered construction of massive new palaces, and became the focus of an even more elaborate courtly culture.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Al-Mu'tasim's reign marked the end of the strong caliphs.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] He strengthened his personal army with the Mamluks and promptly restarted the war with the Byzantines.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Though his attempt to seize Constantinople failed when his fleet was destroyed by a storm, his military excursions were generally successful, culminating with a resounding victory in the Sack of Amorium.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] From the ninth century onward, the Abbasids found they could no longer keep together a centralized polity from Baghdad, which had grown larger than that of Rome.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] As mentioned, Harun al-Rashid had already granted the province of Ifriqiya to the Aghlabids, who ruled this region as an autonomous vassal state until its fall to the Fatimids in 909.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] In al-Ma'mun's reign, Tahir ibn Husayn (al-Ma'mun's general in the civil war) was appointed viceroy of Iran and most of the eastern regions of the empire from 821 onward.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] His descendants, the Tahirids, continued to govern in this position with significant autonomy until 873, although they remained loyal to the caliph and used only the title of *amir*.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] From their capital at Nishapur, they were important patrons of Arabic literature and Sunni religious scholarship, in addition to making major improvements to agriculture.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] In Transoxiana, the Persian Samanids of Bukhara and Samarkand ruled as local governors, initially under the Tahirids.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] They oversaw the development of the region's cities into major trade centers, profiting from long-distance trade between China, Central Asia, Eastern Europe, and the Middle East.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] 847–861) was characterized by the caliph's extravagant spending, his attempts to further consolidate power within the state, and his replacement of the *Mihna* policy with support for more orthodox Sunni scholars, in particular the Hanbali school.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] In 853, the Byzantines sacked Damietta in Egypt, and the caliph responded by sending troops into Anatolia, who sacked and marauded until they were eventually annihilated in 863.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Al-Mutawakkil's lifestyle and spending weakened his support among the military.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] In 861, he was murdered at a party by a group of Turkish soldiers.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] This was the first time the Abbasid military intervened so directly and violently at court and it set a precedent for further coups.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The following period, sometimes known as the "Anarchy at Samarra" (861–870), saw four different caliphs come and go.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] While they each attempted to reassert their authority, they were at the mercy of military and political factions.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Tax collection lapsed and, along with al-Mutawakkil's previous spending, this left the state short on funds, which exacerbated the infighting.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] In 865, the Turkish soldiers of Samarra even besieged Baghdad to overthrow the caliph al-Musta'in and, when the city fell the following year, they replaced him with al-Mu'tazz.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The latter was overthrown by the same faction in 869 and replaced by al-Muhtadi, who was similarly overthrown in 870.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Al-Muhtadi was succeeded by al-Mu'tamid, who was finally able to restore some order, in large part thanks to the help of his brother al-Muwaffaq, who kept the military under control and ran most government affairs.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The restoration was hampered by the Zanj rebellion, which erupted in 869 and threatened the center of Abbasid control in Iraq.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] This major threat was not brought under control until a determined campaign was launched in 879.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] By the 870s, Egypt became autonomous under Ahmad ibn Tulun and his Tulunid successors, though they continued to acknowledge the caliph and generally sent tribute to Baghdad.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] For a time, they even controlled Syria and parts of the Jazira (Upper Mesopotamia).
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] In 882, the caliph al-Mu'tamid even tried to move his residence to Egypt at Ibn Tulun's invitation, though this move was aborted by the intervention of al-Muwaffaq.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] In the east, the Saffarids were former soldiers in the Abbasid army who were stationed in Sistan and remained there as local strongmen.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] They began to challenge the Tahirids from 854 onward and in 873 they captured Nishapur, ending Tahirid rule.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] They marched on Baghdad in 876 but were defeated by al-Muwaffaq.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The two sides were forced to come to terms and the Abbasids allowed the Saffarids to rule over Sistan, Fars, Kirman, and Khurasan.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] In 898, al-Mu'tadid set the Saffarids and Samanids against each other by formally endorsing a Saffarid claim over Transoxiana, the Samanid domain.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The Samanids emerged triumphant in battle and were able to expand their control thenceforth to Khurasan, while the Saffarids were contained further south.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The Samanids never threatened Iraq or western Iran, but they were also not as close to the caliphs as their Tahirid predecessors and in practice they were almost entirely independent of Baghdad.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] They became even greater patrons of religion and the arts than the Tahirids.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] They still maintained an orthodox Sunni ideology but they differed from their predecessors by promoting the Persian language.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] There was a brief Abbasid political and military revival at the end of the 9th century, especially under the policies of caliphs al-Mu'tadid (r.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Under al-Mu'tadid, the capital was moved from Samarra back to Baghdad.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Incursions by the Qarmatians and allied Bedouin tribes posed a serious threat from 899 onwards, but the Abbasid army, led by Muhammad ibn Sulayman, won a reprieve against them in 904 and 907.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] In 905, the same general invaded Egypt and overthrew the weakened Tulunids, re-establishing Abbasid control to the west.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] By the time caliph al-Muktafi died in 908, the Abbasid revival was at its peak and a strong centralized state was in place again.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] After his death, however, the state became dominated by feuding bureaucrats.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] 908–932), the Abbasid court continued to project power and wealth publicly but the politics and financial policies of the time compromised the caliphate's sustainability in the long-term.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] It was in this period that the practice of giving out *iqta*s (fiefs in the form of tax farms) as favours began, which had the effect of reducing the caliphate's own tax revenues.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] In 909, North Africa was lost to the Fatimid dynasty, an Isma'ili Shia sect tracing its roots to Muhammad's daughter Fatima.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The Fatimids took control of Ifriqiya from the Aghlabids and eventually conquered Egypt in 969, where they established their capital, Cairo, near Fustat.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] By the end of the century, they were one of the main political and ideological challenges to Sunni Islam and the Abbasids, contesting the Abbasids for the titular authority of the Islamic *ummah*.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The challenge of the Fatimid Caliphate only ended with their downfall in the 12th century.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] 934–941), Baghdad's authority declined further as local governors refused to send payments to the capital.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The Ikhshidids ruled Egypt and Syria autonomously prior to the Fatimid takeover.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Even in Iraq, many governors refused to obey and the caliph was unable to send armies against them.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Al-Radi was forced to invite the governor of Wasit, Muhammad ibn Ra'iq, to take over the administration under the newly created position of *amir al-umara* ("Commander of Commanders").
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Ibn Ra'iq disbanded the salaried army of the caliph and reduced much of the government's bureaucratic infrastructure, including the traditional vizierate, thus removing much of the Abbasid state's basis for power.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] He was overthrown in 938 and the following years were bogged down in political turmoil.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Al-Mustakfi had a short reign from 944 to 946, and it was during this period that the Persian faction known as the Buyids from Daylam swept into power and assumed control over the bureaucracy in Baghdad.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] According to the history of Miskawayh, they began distributing *iqta*s to their supporters.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] This period of localized secular control was to last nearly 100 years.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Mahmud of Ghazni took the title of sultan, as opposed to the *amir* that had been in more common usage, signifying the Ghaznavid Empire's independence from caliphal authority, despite Mahmud's ostentatious displays of Sunni orthodoxy and ritual submission to the caliph.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] In the 11th century, the loss of respect for the caliphs continued, as some Islamic rulers no longer mentioned the caliph's name in the Friday *khutba*, or struck it off their coinage.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Despite the power of the Buyid amirs, the Abbasids retained a highly ritualized court in Baghdad, as described by the Buyid bureaucrat Hilal al-Sabi', and they retained a certain influence over Baghdad as well as religious life.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] As Buyid power waned with the rule of Baha' al-Daula, the caliphate was able to regain some measure of strength.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The caliph al-Qadir, for example, led the ideological struggle against the Shia with writings such as the *Baghdad Manifesto*.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The caliphs kept order in Baghdad itself, attempting to prevent the outbreak of *fitna*s in the capital, often contending with the *ayyarun*.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] With the Buyid dynasty on the wane, a vacuum was created that was eventually filled by the dynasty of Oghuz Turks known as the Seljuqs.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] By 1055, the Seljuqs had wrested control from the Buyids and Abbasids, and took temporal power.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] When the amir and former slave Basasiri took up the Shia Fatimid banner in Baghdad in 1056–57, the caliph al-Qa'im was unable to defeat him without outside help.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Toghril Beg, the Seljuq sultan, restored Baghdad to Sunni rule and took Iraq for his dynasty.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Once again, the Abbasids were forced to deal with a military power that they could not match, though the Abbasid caliph remained the titular head of the Islamic community.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The succeeding sultans Alp Arslan and Malikshah, as well as their vizier Nizam al-Mulk, took up residence in Persia, but held power over the Abbasids in Baghdad.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] When the dynasty began to weaken in the 12th century, the Abbasids gained greater independence once again.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] 1118–1135) was the first caliph to build an army and to lead it in battle since the 10th century.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] He recruited Kurdish and Arab Bedouin tribes and re-fortified Baghdad.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] His first concern was not the Seljuks but the Mazyadids of Hilla in central Iraq, whom he met in battle in 1123.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] His bid for independence was ultimately unsuccessful, as he was defeated by a Seljuk army in 1135 and assassinated soon after.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] 1136–1160), a new caliphal state began to emerge with the help of his vizier Ibn Hubayra.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Ibn Hubayra concentrated on reasserting authority in Iraq while the Seljuk Empire deteriorated.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The Abbasids successfully defended Baghdad against the Seljuqs in the siege of 1157 and then conquered their Mazyadid enemies in Hilla in 1162.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] By the end of al-Muqtafi's reign, Baghdad controlled a state stretching from Basra in the south to the edges of Mosul in the north.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] After over two hundred years of Abbasid subjection to foreign dynasties, Caliph al-Mustanjid (r.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] 1160–1170) formally declared independence from the Seljuk sultans in 1165, when he dropped their names from Abbasid coinage.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Initially, the caliphs were still vulnerable to the power of the viziers, but al-Mustadi (r.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] 1170–1180) was able to further rally some support from the Baghdad public as well as symbolic support abroad from the Ayyubid sultan Saladin and the Rum Seljuk sultan Kilij Arslan II.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] 1180–1225) marked a definitive shift in late Abbasid power.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] He reinvigorated public displays of caliphal prestige, removed officials who were too powerful, engaged in diplomacy with regions beyond Iraq, and extended his control over former Seljuk territories in western Iran — including Isfahan, Hamadan, Qazvin and Zanjan.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] He sought to build up his influence among Muslim rulers abroad largely through the Sufi-inspired *futuwwa* brotherhood that he headed.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] 1226–1242), the Abbasid state achieved significant stability and many of the same policies continued.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] He built the Mustansiriyya Madrasa, inaugurated in 1234, the first madrasa to teach all four Sunni *maddhab*s (schools of jurisprudence) and the first madrasa commissioned by an Abbasid caliph.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] In 1206, Genghis Khan established a powerful dynasty among the Mongols of Central Asia.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] During the 13th century, this Mongol Empire conquered most of the Eurasian land mass, including both China in the east and much of the old Islamic caliphate and the Kievan Rus' in the west.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] In 1252, Hulagu Khan, a grandson of Genghis Khan and brother of the new Mongol ruler, Möngke Khan, was placed in charge of a new western campaign to the Middle East that would culminate in the conquest of Baghdad in 1258.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] In the years leading up the Mongol invasion, Baghdad's strength was sapped by political rivalries, sectarian tensions between Sunnis and Shias, and damaging floods.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] In 1257, after destroying the Assassins in Iran, Hulagu wrote to the Abbasid caliph, al-Musta'sim, demanding his submission.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The caliph refused, with Hulagu's status as a non-Muslim (unlike the earlier Buyids and Seljuks) likely a factor.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] There followed months of diplomacy, during which the Mongols may have been informed of Baghdad's weakness by correspondence with the caliph's vizier, Ibn al-Alqami, a Shia who was later accused of colluding with them.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The Mongols began their siege of the city on 29 January 1258.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] On 10 February, al-Musta'sim agreed to meet with Hulagu, who demanded that the caliph order the defenders to stand down and come out of the city in exchange for mercy.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The caliph complied, but the Mongols slaughtered the population and then began the sack of the city on 13 February.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Contemporary accounts describe destruction, looting, rape, and killing on a massive scale over many days, with hundreds of thousands killed and the city reduced to near-empty ruins, though some, like the Christian and Shia communities, were spared.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The Mongols feared rumours that a supernatural disaster would strike if the blood of al-Musta'sim, a direct descendant of Muhammad's uncle and part of a dynasty that had reigned for five centuries, was spilled.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] As a precaution and in accordance with a Mongol taboo against spilling royal blood, Hulagu had al-Musta'sim wrapped in a carpet and trampled to death by horses on 20 February 1258.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The caliph's immediate family was also executed, with the lone exceptions of his youngest son who was sent to Mongolia and a daughter who became a slave in the harem of Hulagu.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The fall of Baghdad marked the effective end of the Abbasid Caliphate.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] It made a deep impression on contemporary and later writers both inside and outside the Muslim world, some of whom created legendary stories about the last caliph's demise.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] It is also traditionally seen as the approximate end to the "classical age" or "golden age" of Islamic civilization.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The events brought profound geopolitical changes to the traditional lands of the Islamic caliphate, with Iraq, Iran, and most of the eastern lands falling under Mongol control while other Muslim rulers retained the lands to the west.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Mongol expansion further west was eventually halted by the Mamluks of Egypt at the Battle of Ain Jalut in 1260, followed by the conflict between the Ilkhanids (Hulagu and his successors) and their Golden Horde rivals, which diverted Mongol attention.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Prior to the Mongol invasion, the later Ayyubid sultans of Egypt had built up an army recruited from slaves, the Mamluks.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] During a political and military crisis in 1250, the Mamluks seized power and established what is now known as the Mamluk Sultanate.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Following the devastation of Baghdad in 1258 and in an effort to secure political legitimacy for the new regime in Egypt, the Mamluk ruler Baybars invited a surviving member of the Abbasid family to establish himself in Cairo in 1260–1261.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The new caliph was al-Mustansir II, a brother of the former caliph al-Mustansir.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] In 1262, he disappeared while leading a small army in an attempt to recapture Baghdad from the Mongols.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Baybars subsequently replaced him with al-Hakim I, another Abbasid family member who had just been proclaimed in Aleppo.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Thereafter, the Abbasid caliphs in Cairo continued to exist as a strictly ceremonial but nonetheless important institution within the Mamluk Sultanate, conferring significant prestige on the Mamluks.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] It continued to be relevant even to other Muslim rulers until the 14th century; for example, the sultans of Delhi, the Muzaffarid sultan Muhammad, the Jalayirid sultan Ahmad, and the Ottoman sultan Bayezid I all sought diplomas of investiture from the caliph or declared nominal allegiance to him.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Caliph al-Musta'in even managed to reign as sultan in Cairo for a brief six months in 1412.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] During the 15th century, however, the institution of the caliph declined in significance.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The last Abbasid caliph in Cairo was al-Mutawakkil III, who was in place when the Ottoman sultan Selim I defeated the Mamluks in 1516 and conquered Egypt in 1517, ending the Mamluk Sultanate.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Selim I met with al-Mutawakkil III in Aleppo in 1516, prior to marching into Egypt, and the caliph was then sent to the Ottoman capital of Constantinople (present-day Istanbul), ending the Abbasid caliphate definitively.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The Abbasids themselves slipped into historical obscurity after this.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The idea of a "caliphate" subsequently became an ambiguous concept that was occasionally revisited by later Muslim rulers and intellectuals for political or religious reasons.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The Ottoman sultans, who were thenceforth the most powerful Muslim rulers in western Asia and the Mediterranean, did not use the title of "caliph" at all before the mid-16th century and only did so vaguely and inconsistently afterwards.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The claim that al-Mutawakkil III "transferred" the office of the caliph to the Ottoman sultan during their meeting in Aleppo is a legend that was elaborated in the 19th century and is not corroborated by contemporary accounts.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The Abbasid historical period lasting to the Mongol conquest of Baghdad in 1258 CE is considered the Islamic Golden Age.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The Islamic Golden Age was inaugurated by the middle of the 8th century by the ascension of the Abbasid Caliphate and the transfer of the capital from Damascus to Baghdad.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The Abbasids were influenced by the Qur'anic injunctions and hadith, such as "the ink of a scholar is more holy than the blood of a martyr", stressing the value of knowledge.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Many classic works of antiquity that would otherwise have been lost were translated into Arabic and Persian and later in turn translated into Turkish, Hebrew and Latin.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] During this period the Muslim world was a cauldron of cultures which collected, synthesized and significantly advanced the knowledge gained from the Roman, Chinese, Indian, Persian, Egyptian, North African, Ancient Greek and Medieval Greek civilizations.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Abbasid literary culture in Iraq reflects long-term Mesopotamian narrative continuities, particularly traditions centered on heroic figures and on barriers separating chaos and order.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Core motifs associated with the Epic of Gilgamesh, mediated through the Alexander Romance, including journeys to the world's limits and the containment of chaos, persisted across religious and political change and continued to circulate in late antique Iraq.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The Babylonian Talmud, composed by Iraq-based rabbis, preserves parallel traditions concerning Gog and Magog and the imagined edges of the world that confine agents of chaos.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Together, these traditions situate elements of Abbasid literature within a Mesopotamian narrative continuum.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The best-known fiction from the Islamic world is *One Thousand and One Nights*, a collection of fantastical folk tales, legends and parables compiled primarily during the Abbasid era.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The collection is recorded as having originated from an Arabic translation of a Sassanian-era Persian prototype, with likely origins in Indian literary traditions.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Stories from Arabic, Persian, Mesopotamian, and Egyptian folklore and literature were later incorporated.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] The epic is believed to have taken shape in the 10th century and reached its final form by the 14th century; the number and type of tales have varied from one manuscript to another.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] All Arabian fantasy tales were often called "Arabian Nights" when translated into English, regardless of whether they appeared in *The Book of One Thousand and One Nights*.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] This epic has been influential in the West since it was translated in the 18th century, first by Antoine Galland.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Many imitations were written, especially in France.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Various characters from this epic have themselves become cultural icons in Western culture, such as Aladdin, Sinbad and Ali Baba.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] A famous example of Islamic poetry on romance was *Layla and Majnun*, an originally Arabic story which was further developed by Iranian, Azerbaijani and other poets in the Persian, Azerbaijani, and Turkish languages.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] It is a tragic story of undying love much like the later *Romeo and Juliet*.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Arabic poetry reached its greatest height in the Abbasid era, especially before the loss of central authority and the rise of the Persianate dynasties.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Writers like Abu Tammam and Abu Nuwas were closely connected to the caliphal court in Baghdad during the early 9th century, while others such as al-Mutanabbi received their patronage from regional courts.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Under Harun al-Rashid, Baghdad was renowned for its bookstores, which proliferated after the making of paper was introduced.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] Chinese papermakers had been among those taken prisoner by the Arabs at the Battle of Talas in 751.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] As prisoners of war, they were dispatched to Samarkand, where they helped set up the first Arab paper mill.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] In time, paper replaced parchment as the medium for writing, and the production of books greatly increased.
[src:maritime-history/abbasid-p01] These events had an academic and societal impact that could be broadly compared to the introduction of the printing press in the West.
